animal.description:
Donate at codysfriendsrescue.org to help us save more lives! https://codysfriendsrescue.org/donate

Diamond just put behind her a long ordeal, surgery and recovery - and is ready to return to some action! She never let her illness, or the surgery dull her shine - and continues right on - learning manners, loving other pups, and loving kids! She really likes going for rides in the car. If you enjoy a smart, fun, energetic young pup - here she is!!!!

CFR has a APBT/Boxer mix that needs a foster/adopter; she is 2 years old, 30 pounds, likes activity. Needs a yard to run in :) She had an injury to a salivary duct probably from being on a chain for a very long time; it was surgically repaired though it took a long time to heal and required that she be kenneled for weeks while infection resolved and salivary glands began working normally; she has been given a clean bill of health. She is friendly to adults and kids and dogs, with proper introduction. and just wants LOVE!!! She would di best with another dog so she can play!

Her vet bills were substantial but her adoption donation is still only $270.63 if you are interested in adopting.

She is very smart, loves to learn, 100% potty trained. She's bell trained for going outside. Knows basic commands - sit, come, and working on stay and walking away. Chooses love and pets and hugs over eating. Absolutely non-resource guarding, willing to share. She can be intrusively excited to meet other dogs so needs calm, controlled introductions. This behavior is not aggressive but rather like an animal who has had little experience with other animals. At the vet she roamed the back offices around a variety of species including other dogs, cats, horses, etc. and there was no aggression or reactivity.

She is a happy soul and appreciative of your time and attention. We think decompression time is important with this pretty little girl.

 

Applications are at https://bit.ly/codys_adoption_application.

Los Angeles - This really big boy is looking for a deafie experienced home.  He has an issue with one eye, I will assess with a specialist shortly.  He is 175lbs or so and his current mom and dad simply cannot keep him any longer.  I have explored options with them over the past month, but they feel surrender is in his best interest. He really is super sweet.  Can get the zoomies and excited.  Still very much a puppy at heart.  Housebroken.  I am going to ask that we keep our comments kind please.  
Family mentioned possible allergy to grass, but only bothers him a few months out of the year.  He has been on Apoquel and Cytopoint at one point.  We will get him on the right track before going to his new home.  Ozone, fecal transplant, better diet.
He really needs proper training as well.  Love isn't enough.  He needs to have boundaries so he doesn't end up in this situation again.  

Male Great Dane deaf and vision impaired in one eye.
3 years old
Goes home neutered, dewormed, microchipped, heartworm tested, tick borne disease screen, blood and chemistry, vaccinated. 
Maybe female Great Dane or other female companion 
No small children.
Cats unknown, other species unknown

For more information, please contact us at Deethenetworker@gmail.com

animal.description:
Hi I'm Minnie! I'm about 5 [to 6] yr old beagle hound mix [weighing it at about 40 pounds]. I know I'm a cutie! I'm in foster care now and I have made so much progress since being with my foster mom. I have gotten off antidepressants and my anxiety level has lowered significantly. Every day I'm becoming more and more balanced dog. 
My foster mom says that I'm excitable, loving, sweet, stubborn at times but who isn't ?. I'm am house trained and walk well on a lease and I'm crate trained. I know basic commands like sit, stay and come. I also am highly food motivated, which is great for training! 
I need a home with other dogs to show me the house rules. I love other dogs and want playmates. I can't be with cats or chickens since I have a high prey drive. 
Since I've been returned once by potential adopters we are making it mandatory that you work with my trainer for a couple free sessions at your home to get me adjusted to my new forever home. 
As amazing as I am and would be a fantastic addition to your family, I need time, patience, structured living, and understanding that at I still get a little nervous but it's workable. Please consider adding me to your family.  If interested, please contact my rescuer Bev at trampsrescue @yahoo.com or 804-248-3042.

animal.description: Hi everyone! Meet Janie! This sweet 1 yr old, small Black Lab mix is looking for her forever home! In her short life, Janie has experienced some trauma and hard times, but this little survivor has turned out to be a very sweet, playful young girl. Because of her background, she is sometimes afraid when meeting new people, but once she bonds with her person, she loves to cuddle and give kisses. Janie is a "dog's dog" and has loved and done well with the dogs in her foster homes. She has a lot of youthful energy and likes to play exuberantly (so she would do best in a home with another dog with similar energy). Although Janie would do best with another well-matched dog, she also plays well by herself. Janie is spayed, is Heartworm negative,current in vaccines,is around 35 lbs, and is housetrained. She is also crate trained, walks well on leash, and loves to play with toys. She is treat-motivated and knows "sit." Janie will do best in a quiet home with no children and with a pet-parent who has patience and can spend time helping Janie become a more socialized, comfortable and confident dog. She is adorable and such a good girl - she just needs a home where she can feel safe and where her human will commit to her ongoing training and growth. If you are interested in adopting Janie, please complete an application at lastdaydogs.com

animal.description:
We cover Illinois, Indiana, Iowa, Kansas, Kentucky, Missouri, Nebraska, Oklahoma and Wisconsin and transportation is available for adoptions within those states. Rocky is currently in WI.

Rocky's temporary foster mom has this to say about him: 
Rocky loves to play with balls. He will bring them to you to be thrown and we throws them for himself. If the ball goes behind the couch he has no problem moving furniture to get them. He can be a bit of a clown. Rocky loves belly rubs and butt scratches. He is not much of a licker, but gets very excited when we come home and will lick our hands. Rocky does love spending time outside in our fenced yard exploring and running around.

Rocky is very smart. He does know sit, stay, drop and no. He does not go on the furniture and has never tried. He does take treats gently and shows no signs of food aggression. We did have one incident where he was resource guarding a bone (growled and snarled), so we distracted him and picked it up and have not allowed him to have any bones since. When we tell him to kennel he will go right in. He enjoys sleeping and resting in his kennel. He is house trained, and only tried to mark in our house once. He did let us bathe him and did very well.

Rocky is a good watch dog. He is very aware of his surroundings and will let out a howl bark when someone is on our property. When he sees the neighbors in their window from our backyard he does wag his tail, so we believe he does like people. 

Rocky did see a cat outside and was very excited. He was barking, play bowing and wagging his tail. But the cat ran away so there was no interaction besides that. He does show interest in my dogs, but I will start to do slow interactions to see how they do like through a gate. 

Rocky will make someone a great pet. You can tell he was well loved in his other home. He is such a fun boy.

FAST FACTS:
*8 Years Old - 29 Pounds
*Lower Energy Level
*Older Children
*Dog Friendly
*No Cats
*Potty/Crate Trained

BIO:
Hi there! My name is Webby and I am a sweet, sassy senior lady who would love a comfy, cozy home to call my own. I would do best in a quiet home with calm humans who understand to go slow with me: I love head and belly rubs, but if you move too quickly I might grumble in surprise; once you start petting me, though, expect to spend some time giving me a massage as I will nudge your hand to encourage you to keep going! Because I can be hand-shy, I prefer older children who understand I like to give permission to be pet. I did fine when I previously met dogs, but no kitty cats for me, please. I'm a pretty mellow lady who enjoys to snooze and lounge in luxury. I'm potty and crate trained, and am ready to relax in my forever home so hurry up and fill out that application!

ADOPTION REQUIREMENTS, NO EXCEPTIONS:
*ADOPTION FEE: $125
*Be at least 21 years of age
*Live in a 50-mile radius of Itasca, within the Illinois border
*Have the knowledge and agreement of all adults living in the household
*Have approval from owner of residence (written in lease)
*Have a valid ID with current address (please provide proof of address if ID address is not up-to-date)
*Be approved as a suitable adoptive home by Fetching Tails Foundation
*Be prepared to make a lifetime commitment

If interested please fill out an application on our website at www.fetchingtailsfoundation.org; please make sure you fill in every required field/question or your submission will not go through. Please note that we take time to learn as much as we can about each dog in our care and our bios are our current observations; we are unable to make any guarantees on the future health or temperament of your adopted dog. Most dogs in our care come with unknown pre-rescue history and as such breed and age estimates are an educated guess.

Please read entire description. Razz and Tazz are brothers in need of a new home. If interested, please complete an application on our website at www.pawswapofgreaterlafayette.com/adopting. If their ad is still viewable, we are still accepting applications. These boys need a fence! Read more below to find out if these 2 could complete your family. 

Meet Razz and Tazz. These handsome boys turned 1 year old on Thanksgiving. They are Yellow Lab / Rottweiler mixes and weigh 66 pounds. They are littermates and have always been together. We would love to try and find them a home together. We would consider separating them, but would like to try the together route first.

Razz and Tazz are very sweet, friendly pups. Razz is a bit more laid-back than his goofy brother. Razz is also a bit more confident. Tazz is fun and willing to drop everything and play! We met this duo recently when their owner has run into some devastating losses that includes family members and ultimately her housing. Their deadline was quickly approaching. We met them and instantly fell in love. Thanks to Pooch at Play, these boys are safe until we can place them in a home.

Razz and Tazz are used to being crated when unsupervised and alone. They would very much enjoy a fenced yard. They have not had experience with cats and really haven't been around other dogs except each other. We are still getting to know their preferences, but they have very sweet personalities and have no aggressive tendencies about them. They did great with their initial vetting and easily handled by the vet staff.

Razz and Tazz are now up to date on vaccines, microchipped, and heartworm negative. They are now on preventatives and awaiting their neuter appointment in early January. We would love to find them a foster or adoptive home in the meantime! Please send us a message if you are interested. Their adoption fee is $150 each. and includes all the vetting. If interested, please complete an application on our website at www.pawswapofgreaterlafayette.com/adopting. If interested in fostering, we provide supplies, you provide the love!

Please read entire description. Riley's adoption fee is $175. We have several requirements for his future home. If you read further and find that you meet those requirements, then please complete an application on our website at www.pawswapofgreaterlafayette.com/adopting. If his ad is still viewable, we are still accepting applications. 

Meet Riley. This drop dead gorgeous pup is around 3 years old and around 50 pounds. He was originally found as a stray. We did locate his owner, but they never came for him. Riley spent his life living in a home without a fenced yard, so during his potty time he was tied out. He ended up becoming an escape artist and was spotted in the area frequently running loose which is how he ended up at the kennel. 

Riley has very typical husky behavior and will need a securely fenced yard and an owner who is experienced with huskies. Riley took some time to warm up to the staff at the kennel and that was one issue his owner spoke about. Riley is sometimes not the best with strangers and especially doesn't like his collar grabbed. Riley has never bitten any one and we would like to keep it that way. There are some easy precautions that can be put in place in a new home to ensure he safely interacts with guests in the home. Riley is a great car rider and really adores the volunteers now. He took a trip recently and went on a walk around campus and was spoiled with a pup cup and loved every second of it. 

Riley lived with kids and is said to be good with other dogs. We would recommend 12+ for Riley and would be happy to set up a meet with any other potential dogs in the home. We are unsure how he does with cats. Riley is neutered, up to date on vaccines, heartworm negative, and microchipped. If interested in meeting this handsome pup, please complete an application on our website at www.pawswapofgreaterlafayette.com/adopting. His adoption fee is $175.

animal.description:
Hello my name is Butch. I am about 1.5 years old and I am quite the Lady's Man. I love to snuggle, hug and kiss. Right now I am living with my foster Mom, Dad & teenage brother. I really love my foster mom and I am slowly starting to warm up to my foster dad & brother. They are trying so hard to win my love and trust but I may never truly give it to them! Because of this, I would like to live in a home without any men so I don't have to share the attention!

My foster mama loves the fact that I am completely potty trained and haven't had one accident in the house. I do love my kennel and sleep all night there and enjoy being in there as it is my safe space. My favorite treat is cheese and I will drool just thinking about getting a piece. I take my treats very gently and wait patiently for my reward. I am very well mannered when it comes to food. I don't steal anything off the counter, table or garbage. I have been venturing out on some walks and I am enjoying Minnesota. My foster mom loves that I don't pull when I walk and stick close by her. I don't bark too much only when I am really scared. I am building confidence and learning so much while I am decompressing from the last month of changes. I really would like to have a strong leader who can be confident in me and teach me to be confident myself. 

Which leads me to tell you a sad story. My owner whom I loved very much unexpectedly passed away last month. This has left me completely heart broken. You can see it in my eyes from time to time. The last month has had so many changes for me. I am working on figuring out a whole new world without my person. I am looking for a new family or person that will let me grieve my loss and heal my broken heart. I am a gentle boy with a giant loyal heart just waiting to find the perfect new family to call my own. 


--------------------------------------------


All our Warrior Dogs will have all age appropriate medical care and vaccines, a microchip, and spay/neuter before adoption unless age is a factor with a puppy younger than 6-12 months at the time of adoption. If that is the case, the spay/neuter will be covered in the adoption fee and the owner will be responsible to have the procedure completed at a Warrior Dog Rescue Veterinarian at the appropriate time.

Please note that the majority of our dogs in rescue are from shelters where they have been found as strays or abandoned. Their breed description is based on our very best educated guess based on physical characteristics and their dispositions. If they came to our rescue as an owner surrender, the breed description will be listed as provided by the previous owner.

Adoption Fee - $450

To apply for this pup, please submit an Adoption Application at http://warriordogrescue.com/adopt/adoption-application/

Charlie Myles is a 4 to 5 year old smaller Irish Wolfhound.  He could be part Deerhound, but his location of origin had only those two breeds on the property.  This is a busy, happy dog and will need exercise daily.  

Charlie Myles is not good with strangers entering the yard or home without you being in attendance.  He is not a Rottweiler, but he is a smart, observant, protector of his home.  

Charlie Myles has had a comprehensive physical.  Two tiny fatty cysts were aspirated and sent to cytology to confirm fat cells.  All records, including blood and chemistry, heartworm and tick borne disease screen, SDMA, vaccinations, neuter and deworm notes all provided .  He has also just had a much needed dental.  Our Charlie Myles is developing cataracts however.  They are not yet opaque but visible.  Please be familiar with the breed.

We are in love with our Charlie Myles.  And we think you will be too.  

For more information, please contact us at Deethenetworker@gmail.com.

animal.description: Blaze is a gorgeous senior, about 8-9 years old, about 60 lbs, that has been in the shelter for a couple of years. He was being boarded by a rescue that dissolved and abandoned him! He is a strong boy, but walks very well on the leash. He is a bit picky with new people, but if he likes you, he likes you right away. If he loves you, he loves you completely and unconditionally. He will wait for you at the door, and will only have eyes for you. He is as loyal as they come. He’s got a bit of a stubborn streak, so he requires an experienced dog owner that knows how to handle a strong personality. But really what he wants the most is a good butt scratch from his people. Seriously, he can be doing anything and if you scratch his butt it’s almost like he is hypnotized! He loves being petted and giving his people kisses too. He really is a loving, playful, silly boy. You may have to come visit this big boy a few times for you both to be comfortable, but once he loves you he will look at you with those sad, soulful eyes and he will have your heart. He must go to an adult only home (18+), where he can be the only pet. A yard would be awesome as he LOVES to roll around in leaves. Even on walks… if he sees a nice pile of leaves, he is all over it… belly up and rolling! He is quite amusing. Please inquire about him today and give this loving senior a chance. After everything he’s been through, he deserves a home for his golden years!!

animal.description: Clay is an 8-9 year old shepherd mix. Clay needs a patient, experienced owner who will be willing to work with him and take time to get to know him and gain his trust. He does have some guarding behaviors, especially with food, that can be managed. This loyal boy has had a hard life, and has grown up in the shelter. He can come across as intimidating and sadly no one has looked beyond that, invested some time in visiting him to win him over and given him a chance.  He is an absolute love with the people he knows and loves, and that understand his boundaries. He loves playing ball, will run around with zoomies when he sees his people, and will shower you with tons of sloppy kisses. We would love to find him a forever home, where he can live out his golden years. He needs a quiet, adult only home, where he can be the only pet. A yard for him to run in and play would be amazing. We know that’s a tall order but you can change his life… and he will change yours with limitless love! You must be willing to visit him multiple times at the shelter. Please don’t let that deter you if you think you can be his family. Please give our boy a chance and inquire about him!

animal.description:
Meet Benny!

Hi, my name is Benny. I'm just a year old, 50 pounds, and I'm looking for an active and energetic family that can keep up with my playful personality. I have some issues with my vision and possibly my hearing, but it doesn't slow me a down a bit and I only run in to the occasional door or table corner when I get really excited. Depth perception is hard with only the one good eye after all! I'm super affectionate, my foster mom says I'm a cat-dog because I try to rub myself against her and press my side in to her legs like a cat. I play really well with the other dogs here and get along great with just everybody, although my age and energy means the other dogs sometimes give me reminders to calm down, but I listen when they do! I'm not so great at listening to the cats, but they're just so neat and interesting and all I want to do is sniff them and say hi, but apparently they don't like that so much so they usually run away from me. But my absolute favorite thing to do is spend time with my humans. As much as possible! I'm happy to nap in my crate while they're at work, but I get pretty sad if they're home and I don't get to be out with them. I'm working on understanding that sometime it's just relax time and that means resting in my crate and not crying to be let out, but GOSH that's hard because I just want to be out WITH them! When I do get sad I can be kinda loud... I might not actually be able to hear exactly how loud I'm being. I CAN hear. My foster mom can tell me to sit and go lay down and I can hear the words and do what she says, but she definitely thinks there's SOMETHING funny about my hearing because of how loud I can be sometimes, and she says my pitch is a little funny too. But I'm learning to be calm in my crate when they're home. I know how to go lay down when I'm told, and you don't even have to TELL me to go to my crate when it's dinner time, I'm already there! I'll sit and wait politely until it's ok to eat my food though because I know good manners are important. I'm still working on my leash manners. I can be a puller, but I'm working on it. There's just so many interesting things out there for me to go investigate, but I'm super smart and want to learn so it will just take some time and patience. Basically, I would love an active family that has the time and energy to work with me and knows how to meet the needs of an energetic and smart boy like me, I'm a hearder, with lots of exercise, both physical and mental. I sure hope I get to meet my new family soon! Is it you?

Albert's Dog Lounge is a transporting dog rescue, meaning that we rescue many of our dogs from high kill shelters in areas of dog overpopulation. We are a specialty rescue focusing primarily on senior and special needs dogs.  The vast majority of our dogs come from the Houston, TX area where we have an entire team of volunteers, coordinators, and fosters. We do also work with local shelters, rescues, and owners.  If you apply for a dog that is currently in our local Houston program, we will work to get your dog transported to WI as quickly as possible. We ask that you have patience during this time of uncertainty and unprecedented dog adoptions nationwide. 

Learn more about Albert's Dog Lounge, our mission, and adoption policies by visiting Albertsdoglounge.org. 

Our process includes an approved application, reference checks, a homevisit, and then a meet and greet with the dog. Adoption fee is $275.

Begin your application process by copying this link into your web browser: https://www.albertsdoglounge.org/apply

WI Dept. Of Agriculture License Number: 474085-DS

animal.description:
Bosley is a 1 year-old tri-color pit/lab who is looking to be somebody’s best friend.  He is the friendliest and happiest dog in the world.  Bosley currently has a great home and used to go to work with his human mom every day, but unfortunately there are now new rules in place that prevent him from coming to work with her.  It is a difficult decision for her to make, but would prefer that Bosley be with someone that can provide him a more suitable lifestyle than being home alone all day, which is not fair to any dog, especially a puppy.   

Bosley is a wonderful dog, loves every single human he meets, loves kids and would like to find a new human that lives an active lifestyle that Bosley could join.  When it comes to humans, he has never met a human he doesn't like.

Bosley needs to be the only dog in the home, so he will not be placed in a home with other dogs.  While he is not reactive and doesn’t lunge at other dogs on the leash, he has displayed signs of not always playing well with others and has shown signs of aggression with his older doggy sibling.  Therefore, he will do best as an only dog.  Although he loves cats, he plays rough as he is still young and most cats tend to not favor his style of playing.  

He is e-collar trained, loves swimming, going for jogs, knows how to sit, stay, come, down, etc ... Bosley is still a puppy, so he is high energy.  If you are looking for a slow, calm, minimal energy dog, Bosley is not the right match for you.  If you are looking for a dog that loves to go for jogs, will play fetch as long as you let him, will go on road trips, camping, etc, Bosley would be perfect, since he has done all of these things with his mom!  While he wouldn’t make the best guard dog (he’s kind of a wimp), he has made his home feel very safe by barking when necessary and doing his best to play the part. 


Please help us get sweet Bosley into a safe, loving forever home!  If you're unable to help by adopting, sharing this post or donating is always appreciated.  Don't forget, Passion for Pitties is a 501(c)(3), so all donations are tax-deductible!…every little bit helps!
 
If you would like to adopt loving Bosley, please fill out an application at www.passionforpitties.com under the “Adorable Adoptables” heading.

[IF DOGS ARE POSTED THAT MEANS THEY ARE AVAILABLE! PLEASE DO NOT EMAIL ASKING IF THEY ARE AVAILABLE. IF THEY ARE POSTED, THEY ARE AVAILABLE — PLEASE MAKE SURE TO FOLLOW WRITTEN INSTRUCTIONS ON HOW TO APPLY TO ADOPT AT THE END OF DOGS BIO]

KITTY MUST GO TO A HOME WITH ANOTHER FRIENDLY DOG** 

Why hewo der! My name is Kitty. I am a 2-year-old, spayed female, Lab/Corgi/Pittie Mix weighing around 25 lbs. I am here because The Cantu Foundation helped rescue me when my owner surrendered me in Mexico. I am house trained and I’m working on my leash etiquette, I need a strong leader when I’m walking! When it comes to crate training, I am not all the way trained on that, but I will hang out in there. I am fully vaccinated.

I am very sweet! I love to cuddle and be in your lap, but also, I have a spunky side! I will play for hours if you give me another pup and I will hold my weight while playing, even with my foster’s 70 lbs. doggo. I have a very loyal and calm demeanor and I bring happiness to any room and anyone that meets me (so my foster says). While I have these amazing qualities, I am is working on my anxiety when leaving the house. I often get nervous when going on walkies and when there are loud noises (just so scary!). This is just outside, I am totally fine indoors where I feel like I’m the queen of the house. My favorite thing to do is to cuddle up into my hoomans arms and watch a movie. I will not leave your side! I am dog friendly, but I need to have a nice introduction with the other doggo. I’ve seen kitties on the street and I am not a fan. I can’t wait to find my furever home, will you be my hooman?
My perfect furever home would be one with love and affection as I just want to spoil you with all of mine! A home with a Furr sibling is a MUST , since I can sometimes be nervous a Furr siblings can bring me comfort. The only thing my foster could see me having anxiety over would possibly be a very loud exterior environment. My adoption fee is $400 and that includes spaying/neutering and vetting care. If you want to take me home, please fill out the form on the website here http://www.thecantufoundation.org/adopt.html

Chestnut 
“Chessie”

*IMPORTANT - Due to the current STAY-AT-HOME Order, which is in effect for all of Ontario and is anticipated to be in place until at least Thursday, February 25, 2021, ALL Adoption Proceedings are considered ON HOLD. Applications, Email correspondence, Telephone Interviews and Reference Checks are still being conducted, but MEET & GREETS and ADOPTIONS are being postponed until Feb 25, 2021 or later in accordance with the province's enhanced enforcement. 

Specifics:
~4 year old Canaan/Husky boy from Saudi Arabia
~Healthy with medium energy, 45-50 lbs, neutered, vaccinated and UTD with parasite prevention
~House trained, crate trained and non-destructive
~Walks well on leash with good recall
~A little shy upon first meetings with new people and other dogs, but warms up quickly

Favourite things:
~Chestnut enjoys playtime with other dogs, as well as adventurous walks
~Chessie loves to eat and thoroughly enjoys a dreamy nap by the fireplace after a yummy meal
~Listening to classical music is one of Chessie's favourite hobbies
~Chestnut delights in receiving lots of praise for mastering new tasks and prefers snuggling over treats

Dreamhome Wishlist:
~ A calm, dog experienced family, who will be able to read Chestnut's body language and understand him.
~ Someone that can be calm yet assertive with Chessie, and provide him with structure, rules and boundaries, and of course patience and love.
~ A home in either a rural or light suburban setting . City life is way too busy and noisy for this boy.
~ An adult-only dwelling. Older teens would be fine if they're calm.
~ A home with or without another balanced dog. If Chestnut will be the only dog in the home, the family should be willing to keep up his social interactions with other dogs in a safe environment i.e.Doggy play dates.
~ Adopters who are physically active and spend a good portion of time outdoors, where Chestnut can get the exercise and mental stimulation he needs.
~ A house with a secure fully-fenced yard, as squirrels can be A-holes and lure him away!
~ Someone who either works from home, or has a schedule that will allow them to not leave Chestnut home alone for more than 3-4 hours per day. (A little longer would be fine if
there's another doggy buddy in the home for company).
~ Ideally, a family willing to feed either a Raw Diet or provide a kibble such as Acana, which has less fillers and uses natural preservatives, and add veggies to Chestnut's diet (i.e. Doggytime Smoothie - recipe will be shared with adopter).

Adoption Application:
Visit www.doggytime.net and click ADOPTION APPLICATION,
fill out all required fields and hit SUBMIT.

animal.description:
BISKIT 

*IMPORTANT - Due to the current STAY-AT-HOME Order, which is in effect for all of Ontario and is anticipated to be in place until at least Thursday, February 25, 2021, ALL Adoption Proceedings are considered ON HOLD. Applications, Email correspondence, Telephone Interviews and Reference Checks are still being conducted, but MEET & GREETS and ADOPTIONS are being postponed until Feb 25, 2021 or later in accordance with the province's enhanced enforcement. 

Specifics:
~Available through Canine Haven Rescue at www.caninehavenrescue.com
~2 year old Canaan/Malinois boy from Saudi Arabia
~Healthy with medium-high energy, around 45 lbs, neutered, vaccinated and UTD with parasite prevention
~House trained, crate trained and non-destructive
~Walks well on leash with good recall
~A little shy upon first meetings with new people and other dogs, but warms up quickly
~Walks and runs with a sideways gait due to a previous injury in Saudi Arabia, but isn't negatively affected by it at present

Favourite things:
~Biskit enjoys playtime with humans and other dogs, as well as adventurous walks and tons of treats
~Biskit loves to eat and thoroughly enjoys a dreamy nap after a yummy meal
~Listening to classical music is one of Biskit's favourite hobbies
~Biskit delights in receiving lots of praise (and often treats) for mastering new tasks
~Since being handsome is important to Biskit, he's quite fond of being brushed and receiving compliments
~Squirrel problem? Not anymore says Biskit! He'll alert you immediately to a squirrel or other critter coming to dine and dash from the bird feeder!

Dreamhome Wishlist:
~ A home in a rural or suburban setting which isn't too noisy or busy.
~ A home with a fully fenced yard.
~ A family without young children (older teens okay).
~ A family who's work schedule would ensure that Biskit isn't left unattended for more than 3-4 hours per day. A reputable dog walker could also be an option if work hours are long.
~ A home with or without another balanced dog to play with and to keep him company while the humans are out.
~ A family willing to ensure that Biskit would get at least 3 good walks per day and plenty of physical and mental stimulation.
~ Someone with previous dog experience, dedicated to continuing Biskit's education and providing consistent rules and boundaries, utilizing force-free methods.
~ Ideally, a family willing to feed either a Raw Diet or provide a kibble such as Acana, which has less fillers and uses natural preservatives, and add veggies to Biskit's diet (i.e. Doggytime Smoothie - recipe will be shared with adopter).
~A family aware that Biskit has had an injury in the past which contributes to his odd gait, and that this injury could potentially cause arthritis or other concerns as the dog ages, which would need to be
addressed with the help of a veterinarian.

Adoption Application:
To apply for Biskit,visit www.caninehavenrescue.com

animal.description:
Zeus is a 4 year old 25lb chihuahua terrier mix. He has finally gotten past all the issues from his past life and ready to start another! He is a very loving boy who loves to sit on a lap and rubbed, yet loves and needs a fenced yard for him to get all his energy out and RUN. His favorite thing is chasing and chewing on tennis balls. Would be best as an only dog or maybe one other. Not sure around cats or children. Perfect for an active couple or single who can keep up with his energy!!

The adoption fee is $250 which includes their age appropriate vaccinations(DA2PP and Bordetella), Dewormer, spay/neuter, microchip, heartworm test as well as the registration of their microchip information to you.

The first step to adopting is to fill out an application for adoption. Once approved we will arrange a time for you to meet the animal you are interested in. If it is a match the adoption can then be completed and you can take home your new furry family member. If it is not a match we will file your approved application and you can wait till you find the perfect match.

animal.description:
*Special Needs* Meet Shasta!!! This little girl was injured and left at the Riverside shelter. She was brought to safety and welcomed into the ARF pack where she has received a lot of TLC and is now able to fully use her back legs and is as fast as can be! Due to her injury Shasta needs to be expressed to use the bathroom. The process is fairly quick and easy once you get the hang of it, usually taking less than a few minutes. Shasta is a typical youngster learning the ropes. She is active, playful, curious and is getting better about leash walking every day. She is an amazing snuggler and prefers to sleep under the covers with you. 

Shasta is almost 2 years old and a fun-sized 25 pounds.

If you think you are the right fit for Shasta, please fill out an application today or contact us with any questions about her care. https://petstablished.com/adoption_form/4362/generic

animal.description:
Please welcome Addie who was brought to safety by a couple of angels all the way from Saudi Arabia. As you can see, this girl is SPECIAL! Addie is approximately 5 years old and 28 pounds. She is good with familiar dogs and older kids.
Even though Addie had her hind limbs taken by an awful human and was dumped in the desert, she did not allow it to break her spirit. She has been through so much yet she doesn't look back and is so loving and gentle. Addie craves to be loved/petted and seeks out the nearest hand.

Addie is happiest when she is making new human friends or sun bathing in the yard. She has an adorable howl for every occasion and will make you smile with her resilient way of doing things Addie style. She is truly an inspiration and magical!
***Addie will need long term diaper changes (around every 5 hours or so) but with some tricks from her foster family it is manageable. She has vision loss in her left eye but it doesn't slow her down!
If you think you might be a match for this special girl or have questions about her care please fill out an application or send us an email at arfadopt@angelsofrawley.org.

animal.description:
Rambo he is so handsome !!! He is such a Dude.. however.... he is a night owl and decides to party every night at 9!

Rambo today...he's a fun guy that LOVES other dogs... any size or type of dog. He's cat friendly, and very very smart. Total lovebug! He will need a special adopter who is willing to continue working with him on learning to trust humans. Rambo will need a home with a fenced yard in order to live his best life.

Just a puppy found at 10 weeks old living under an abandoned house. It took a few days to get this guy. Just a baby, not familiar with human touch but so sweet and innocent. His story begins now...his name is Rambo and he got checked out by our vets like all young pups should and now he is on to a safe, comfortable foster home to gain some confidence and get ready to find his forever home.

All Dallas DogRRR adoptable pets are spayed or neutered, microchipped, and up to date on vaccines upon finalizing adoption. The standard minimum donation for puppies is $325 + 8.25% tax = $351.81, for dogs over 12 months the adoption fee is $225 + 8.25% tax = $243.66 and for our senior dogs 8 years and up is $100 + 8.25% tax = $108.25; this increase includes sales tax recently required by the State of Texas to collect. You can view all the adoptable pets and fill out an adoption application online on our website at http://dallasdogrrr.org. 

For more information, you can email adopt@dallasdogrrr.org. Upon receiving your application please allow us 2-3 business days to review and process.

Important Notes: With a Partner Rescue

Hi I'm Anna! I originally came to the rescue just a day away from a bad fate - I'd ended up at a rural county shelter...no longer wanted by my previous owner...a bully breed, pregnant and an owner surrender - that is not a recipe for success in getting out of a shelter. But, thankfully this rescue heard about me and had a foster home available for getting a sweet girl like myself safe and sound. 

While in rescue I gave birth to 9 gorgeous puppies (they get it from me) and I was a good mommie. All of my puppies have been adopted and now its my turn to find my happily ever after. 

I'm a gorgeous girl but I enjoy being active and would like an owner who is regimented and enjoys being active too. Im still working on my leash walking and I get overly excited when I see another dog so I could use some positive reinforcement training and a confident handler owner to help teach me this. 

A fenced yard would be great - of course dogs need to burn off energy going on walks but while getting my training situated, a fenced yard would be great for me to run and play. Don't get me wrong as much as I love to be active what i really love more is to snuggle with my person. 

I'm a great medium sized pup to have by your side and will loyally love you forever. I like some dogs but there are some that I am unsure about so I would need to be properly introduced. With love, patience, and a consistent owner, I'm going to be a great addition to your family!

If you are interested in Anna please make a note in your adoption application….

www.wherethewildthingsarerescue.com

Adoption Fee $300

Spartacus has spent the last few years of his life either as a stray or in and out of shelters. Although each facility tried their best to care for his needs, Sparty does have breed-specific maintenance that could have been better tended to. With small changes in grooming, nutrition, and a transition into a comfortable foster home, he has made huge improvements in his health and appearance. Spartacus would be best in an adult only home with no pets, since true to his breed, he tends to get a little jealous of others getting the love that he needs (after all, he's a big dude! so he SHOULD get more love than everyone else, right?). He is happiest getting fold scratches, smush rubs, and bear hugs from his humans and will let you know with a boof or two if he's waiting on you. He also requires pretty much the same grooming as bulldogs (fold cleaning, foot soaks, nose butter, etc) just on a larger scale.

Little Quaid ? is home with his loving fosters, and we’ve figured out a little bit more about his longterm needs. Yes, he is a typical spicy, Frenchie puppy who loves to get into all sorts of places he doesn’t belong and is VERY chatty. But he’ll need a very special home who can provide for his everyday needs and keep and eye on him:? ? ? Quaid will need to be handfed several small meals of special canned food throughout the day? ? ? So, needless to say, his family has to be able to be with him most of the day for feeding and to monitor any changes ? ? ? He’ll need to be watched like a hawk. Quaid would LOVE to (and will) steal your sandwich and try to swallow it in one bite like a snake, but this is a really bad thing for a fragile boi ? ? ??Because of his genetic issues that went untreated up until now, he’ll always be a special boy. His family needs to be able to commit financially to his lifelong vet visits, pricey diet, and potential emergencies ? ? ?? With that said, Quaid is equal parts spunk and snug and is worth the extra time and love. ? If you think your home might be right for our special little guy, please visit our site to fill out an adoption app. Please also make sure to let us know in your app if you’re willing and able to take on his needs.

animal.description:
Hi, my name is Buddy and that is exactly what I want us to be, buddies. I want you to know a bit about my history. I had a family but when they could no longer care for me so they brought me to a shelter. I was rescued from that shelter but then instead of working on finding me a home, the rescue kept me in a small crate for over a year. There was no attention, no doggie friends or ways to get out and have fun, no exercise, it was terrible. Finally I was put in a foster home but now that I had freedom I wanted to go out and explore so I found a way over the fence. Well, that got me in a lot of trouble so I ended up back at the bad place with the small crate. Finally someone convinced them to send me BACK to the original shelter where all of this started so that at least I would have more room and might finally get a home with people who would love me and take good care of me.

Next, a big group of people heard about my story and they got together and rescued me (for real this time) because they felt I was worth saving. I went to some really great people who have been working with me on being a well-behaved boy. Being confined in such a small place for so long, and isolated as well, would make anyone a little insecure. Either I was not taught basic obedience or I forgot so when I get excited. I can sometimes jump, but now that I am getting regular attention and exercise I am getting better every day. At this point I walk best on a leash when a head collar / halti is used but I have only been out of the shelter for a couple of weeks. I am also learning to be around other dogs again because I have not had friends in so long. Now I do well with other canines as long as things don't get overly excited (this also means no unaltered doggie companions) and squeaky high-pitched talk is too exciting too. The good people continue to work with me and they are teaching me to avoid or ignore. I play with other doggies sometimes (male and female) and seek out some on my own, I even have a girlfriend. Overall, I am somewhat selective with other dogs so definitely no unaltered males. I come with free trainer consultation.I really am a good boy and I look to my human for proper guidance and I take correction well and quickly. Right now (while in training) I am in a very active household with four teenagers with all kinds of crazy animals on the farm. I do wonderfully with kids but could accidentally knock a smaller child down. I am good with cats, have been around chickens and other animals while on leash but they were pretty boring. If you are interested in learning more about me, or to meet me, please email Virginia at; virginiaz3@gmail.com

Age: 4 years
Weight: 45 lbs
Vetting: neutered , up to date on vaccines, heartworm negative
Temperament: Selective with dogs, ok with kids, ok with cats
Training: crate trained, house trained, knows commands

Email for questions: virginiaz3@gmail.com

animal.special_needs_notes: Danica suffered some kind of trauma. We are not sure how she was injured. She has no control of her bladder or bowels.  Her back legs are a little wobbly but that doesn’t slow her down at all. When she is in the house she wears a diaper. When we are outside or on a walk she doesn’t wear one. She tries to potty on her own but she can’t always control her body. She hardly ever messes in the house but during the night when she is asleep she usually has a bit of a mess in her crate. She is the sweetest dog. She loves to go for walks and has not meet a person or dog she didn’t like. She likes to chase cats but never to hurt them. She needs a special home who doesn’t mind that she needs to wear diapers or may leave a mess. She will be spayed the end of January before she goes to her new home. animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Bobbie

is a sweet but cautious 5-pound senior chihuahua boy who was rescued from a hoarding situation with 4 other dogs. he has become quite healthy since arriving and now looks forward to being held though still shy. Bobbie will do well with a small breed savvy person who works from home or is retired and has the time to help him come out of his shell and feel safe. He does need other dog-friendly dogs as he has only ever been a part of a large pack, and he likes to have a pack to feel safe. if you do not already have a dog and are open to adopting two, we have other seniors he came with and a 4-year-old he is buddies with.

Bobbie is pee pad trained and will go outdoors if accompanied. he is not used to the cold and wet and must be bundled up before going out to potty.

Bobbie is being fed a Human grade-Canine diet for his health and longevity. we educate all adopters on canine-specific feeding and care.

PLEASE do not write and ask if this dog is available. If she is listed, he is available. We are 1.25 people who are volunteers and we work 20 hour days and have dozens of applications to review on top of the hundred other things necessary to run a rescue and adoption operation. To fill out an application to adopt Please use this link, You will need a computer to complete as cell phones will drop the application

http://rompinpawsrescue.rescuegroups.org/forms/

The site will ask you to create a password and will send you an email. For ease of use, just use the password they create for you and save that password. This will ensure you have access and can fill out the application.

animal.description:
PLEASE VISIT OUR WEBSITE AT WWW.PITRESCUE.ORG FOR INFORMATION ON OUR ORGANIZATION, ADOPTION POLICIES AND PROCESS, EDUCATIONAL INFORMATION, AND A FULL LIST OF OUR ADOPTABLE DOGS ALONG WITH PHOTOS AND FULL BIOS!!!
More pictures and info on this particular dog visit: https://www.pitrescue.org/brigid

Apply online: http://fs22.formsite.com/siouxempire/form1/index.html?1316620486706

*Adoption application must be filled out with home visit and references (personal and vet) required prior to any adoption. Filling out an application does not obligate you to adopt, but merely begins the process. SEPR DOES adopt out of state!

Adoption fees: All SEPR adoptions are $300 for adults and $400 for puppies 1 year and under.  This includes: adoption fee (spay/neuter, utd vaccinations, micro-chipping), microchip registration, Gentle Leader, and two tie downs for use in your home. 

SEPR requires all adopted dogs attend a training class with their adoptive family within 90 days of their adoption. If an adoptive family completes this training class, they will be refunded $100 of their adoption fee with proof of licensed certificate. SEPR even offers an obedience class called Train-A-Bull to alumni over 1 year of age on a seasonal basis.  These classes are currently free!

*All other pets in the residence must be spayed or neutered and all pets up to date on vaccinations.

*SEPR requires all applicants must be 21 years of age.

*SEPR dogs are adopted to be inside the home, “part of the family” dogs only.

*Families with children 5 years of age and under wanting to adopt puppies will be reviewed on a case by case basis. Raising a puppy properly takes a lot of time, and we understand that in families with small children, time can be a limited commodity.

Meet King! This handsome young Beagle mix was recently surrendered to Worthy Dog by his family. The family was moving and said they could not take him. We think not keeping King is their loss and will be some lucky family's gain. King is a confident, social, and snuggly pup who will make a great family dog. He's lived with kids and LOVES other dogs.

King is currently fostered in SC with a mom, a dad, a teenage boy, two dogs, and a cat. He LOVES both of the dogs and is always trying to get them to play with him. He's more energetic than they are, so we think a young, active dog playmate would be the best fit for him. NO cats, however! He is overly interested in the cat and wants to chase it. We could see King as an only dog, too, as long as his family makes sure he gets regular doggie play dates and has doggie friends. He really enjoys other dogs and wants to play and have fun.

His foster mom describes King as a moderate-to-active energy dog. He settles down if he gets enough exercise and can be chill inside the home. He definitely needs a fun, active family to entertain him. He's also a champion snuggler and will always choose to be curled up next to you on the couch and under a blanket, enjoying the added warmth if given the option. King is both house trained and crate trained, and he does well meeting new people. He has decent leash walking skills and listens well to verbal commands. He has learned to sit on command and will, most of the time, stay when asked.

King has been happy and welcoming to everyone he's met. He came from a home with kids, and his foster family has seen him around young kids as well. We think he'll be a great addition to most families - preference will be given to active families with another young dog playmate in the home.

Apply today!

BREED ESTIMATE: Beagle Mix (low rider)
GENDER: Male
APPROXIMATE WEIGHT: 27 lbs
APPROXIMATE AGE: ~ 2 years
COAT TYPE: short
ADOPTION FEE: $400
OTHER INFO: utd on shots/neutered/microchipped
LOCATION: Alexandria, VA

FOR MORE INFO OR TO ADOPT: Please go to https://adopt.worthydog.org and complete the application.

You can also help save dogs like this one by becoming a foster, providing a rescue dog with a temporary home and giving them the love and care they need until they are permanently adopted. Every person who fosters is directly responsible for saving the life of a dog, because we can only save as many dogs as we have foster families available to welcome them into their homes. If you think you might be interested in becoming a foster and want to learn more, please go to https://foster.worthydog.org and fill out an application.

Worthy Dog Rescue is an all-volunteer, foster-based rescue that primarily adopts to families in the DC Metro area.

animal.description:
My name is Jax. My family was unable to keep me and asked JR's to find me a good home. When I first arrived, I was sweet with everyone, but then I realized my family left and I become very scared and nervous. I didn't want anyone to touch me. I was sad and depressed and a bit scary. One day a foster came to the facility and said "I am taking him home tonight and we're going to figure it out". We had a great car ride home! I sat nicely in the back seat. When we got home, I met "the pak". She had a Doberman (foster) and a bunch of Rottweilers and 2 little old scruffy dogs. They were all quite welcoming and we playing in the yard. Then I met the kitties. They are interesting and fun to chase...but that's about it. I would do best in an adult-only home, and because my temperament is very true-to-breed, my family will have had ChowChow experience before. 

I am completely house trained and trustworthy in the house. I do not chew things up. I do not jump on furniture or counter surf (there's a sassy Rottweiler here that does that!). I love my people and I love to be pet. I've been here for over 2 weeks now and I know I can be a good boy in a home. I was just groomed and feel SOOO good!

I am hoping my furever family finds me soon. This place is great, but I know I have a furever to find of my own! 


Adoption fee: $350
 
Adoption fees for all dogs/puppies include a $50 refundable training deposit. Complete your basic training program and provide a copy of the certificate within 4 months (120 days) of adoption and we will refund $50 of the original adoption fee.
 
All dogs/puppies have been fully vetted including spay/neuter, micro-chipping, worming, heartworm testing and preventative treatment, flea/tick preventative, and all required age appropriate vaccinations. As required by Wisconsin Act 90, all dogs will have received a veterinarian exam (CVI) within the past 30 days.
 
Our adoption process requires the submission of an application. Applications and Adoption Rules can be found on our website, on the "HOW TO ADOPT" tab at JRsPupsNStuff.org. Upon receipt of the completed application, we will process the application including: contact with your veterinarian and completion of a home visit. Please be sure to include the contact information for your vet as we will call. If your vet requires an information release, please be sure to contact them as soon as you submit your application. We are a group of volunteers with families and jobs, so please be patient and allow a few days for our response.
 
JR's Pups-N-Stuff Dog Sellers License 270089-DS

Background:  Maisy is a purebred AKC-registered Lab, originally from Montana.   Trained as a field trial dog, she is full of spirit and energetic.  She cannot sit still.  Her “play” switch is ON all the time.  
 
Maisy retrieving the dummies -- https://youtu.be/iQaPyQiD_4E 
Maisy and the squeaky chicken -- https://youtu.be/2q6SBB1vs3Y 
Maisy and Rookie loving the rope-tug -- https://youtu.be/8IzozncPNcc 
 
What Maisy’s owner says:  
We purchased her when she was six-months-old and planned to cross breed her with one of our own Labs.  We produce one litter of Lab pups every few years.  But Maisy’s anxieties have caused us to rethink breeding her.  She shows some OCD-like behavior when in her outside kennel and garage crate… by spinning in circles.  She does not sit still long enough to allow you to touch her – always in motion.  In addition, she has demonstrated some snarkiness (growling) at our other female Labs.  

Maisy is fine with our male Labs and spends hours running around with them and playing rope pull.  While we have not used Maisy for hunting, she is able to retrieve bumpers/dummies per field trial standards.  Maisy has never been around children or cats, but she has spent time with horses.  We had her try out as a police detection canine but she was too anxious around motorcycles and that was a non-starter.  Given her over-the-top high-energy we have not allowed her to roam freely inside our home – so she is likely not house-trained.  
 
What Maisy’s Rescue Rep says:  
Maisy will do best in a home with lots of room to run and exercise.  Definitely not a city dog.  May not even be a suburbia dog.  Maisy’s ideal adopter is an outdoors-person who loves to hunt and fish, who snowshoes in the winter, who hikes in the mountains in the summer, and who needs a devoted four-legged side-kick.  Ranch life would be wonderful for Maisy.  Not for the timid at heart; not for the couch-potato doggie-snuggler; not for those inexperienced with energized American field labs.  
 
Medical:  Maisy is in great shape.  She received an excellent grade for her OFA hip radiograph.  Maisy is current on distemper vax and microchipped, but due for a Rabies vax and needs to be spayed.  
 
Maisy is located in:  Sebastopol.
 
If you are interested in Maisy, please contact Rescue Rep Dave at 415-686-4248 or david.c.ely@sbcglobal.net

animal.description: My name is Cinnamon and I'm looking for my forever home!. I'm 8 years old and petite. Until just a few weeks ago, I lived at a commercial breeding facility making puppies. Now that I've "retired" from that life, I'd love to have a warm and cuddly home of my own! Things I love: treats - especially human foods - sniffing all the sniffs on walks, and exploring new spaces. And lots and LOTS of pets, kisses, and cuddles from my humans. If you stop petting me, even for even a second, I may climb on your lap for more attention. I like to follow my people around the house like a little shadow, but I also love a good nap in a comfy spot on the couch. Things I DO NOT like:  the other pups in my foster home. You see, I'd really like to have the human attention all to myself. I also dislike toys that squeak. Foster mom says that I'm a very smart girl and already know how to come when called, but my forever family will need to continue to work on formal commands like sit/stay/off and how to use stairs (I'm a bit of a klutz going up and down stairs - I mean, who would blame me - I never knew what they were until a few weeks ago!). I am currently being fostered in Milwaukee, WI. If you live in the midwest and think you might have the perfect lap for me to sit on, visit www.savingshibas.com/adopt to download an application to become an approved SIRA adopter.

animal.description:
PLEASE VISIT OUR WEBSITE AT WWW.PITRESCUE.ORG FOR INFORMATION ON OUR ORGANIZATION, ADOPTION POLICIES AND PROCESS, EDUCATIONAL INFORMATION, AND A FULL LIST OF OUR ADOPTABLE DOGS ALONG WITH PHOTOS AND FULL BIOS!!!
More pictures and info on this particular dog visit: https://www.pitrescue.org/brigid

Apply online: http://fs22.formsite.com/siouxempire/form1/index.html?1316620486706

*Adoption application must be filled out with home visit and references (personal and vet) required prior to any adoption. Filling out an application does not obligate you to adopt, but merely begins the process. SEPR DOES adopt out of state!

Adoption fees: All SEPR adoptions are $300 for adults and $400 for puppies 1 year and under.  This includes: adoption fee (spay/neuter, utd vaccinations, micro-chipping), microchip registration, Gentle Leader, and two tie downs for use in your home. 

SEPR requires all adopted dogs attend a training class with their adoptive family within 90 days of their adoption. If an adoptive family completes this training class, they will be refunded $100 of their adoption fee with proof of licensed certificate. SEPR even offers an obedience class called Train-A-Bull to alumni over 1 year of age on a seasonal basis.  These classes are currently free!

*All other pets in the residence must be spayed or neutered and all pets up to date on vaccinations.

*SEPR requires all applicants must be 21 years of age.

*SEPR dogs are adopted to be inside the home, “part of the family” dogs only.

*Families with children 5 years of age and under wanting to adopt puppies will be reviewed on a case by case basis. Raising a puppy properly takes a lot of time, and we understand that in families with small children, time can be a limited commodity.

animal.description: Christmas #7432 AKA Chrissy is an adorable 6-year-old female Hound/Shepherd mix. Chrissy loves to know what you are up to and wants to help! She absolutely loves playtime. Her favorite toys are stuffed animals, tennis balls and squeaky toys. Chrissy loves to snuggle as well, but given the choice, she loves to be outdoors. She is very eager to learn and is treat-motivated. Chrissy should be fed separately from other animals in the home. She is crate trained, although it takes a bit of coaxing to get her inside. She is house trained. Chrissy can get up to mischief if left to her own devices, so be sure to crate her when you are not home! This beautiful momma came to us with 11 adorable pups in tow. While she is a great mom, Christmas is ready for some much-needed R&R and a home of her own. She weighs 50 pounds and is full grown. This pup is microchipped. We believe you can always teach an ‘old’ dog new tricks, so we highly recommend continued obedience training for this smart pup; it stimulates the dog's mind and establishes a good dog/adopter relationship. This pup, like all pups, should be on heartworm preventative; an ounce of prevention is worth a pound of cure. If you are interested in adopting this dog, and are already approved to adopt through our organization, please contact dogs@lastchanceanimalrescue.org with the pup’s name and ID number in the subject line. OTHERWISE, please submit an adoption application online: http://www.lastchanceanimalrescue.org/adoptus.html E-mail dogs@lastchanceanimalrescue.org with questions. Stay tuned to our Facebook page for updates: www.facebook.com/LCARMD #adoptlove #PicMe #petsmartcharities

animal.description:
Hi! My name is Sarah. I’m a healthy four year old GSD/Husky mix. I’m a petite girl weighing in at about 50 pounds. I have a thick, soft coat and have one brown eye and one blue eye.

I have a confident and somewhat aloof demeanor. I like to take my time to get to know new friends. Once we’ve spent some time together I will happily approach for pets

I have nice easy energy and will make a terrific addition to a moderately active home; I like to get out and about and I do great on leash. I ride nicely in the car too. Walks, beach time and camping trips are some of my favorite activities.

I like other “regular-sized” dogs but have an energetic play style that may be too much for dogs that don’t like to play or for older dogs. True to my breeds, I have a tendency to nip at the feet of other dogs. Some dogs may not appreciate that. I also like to chase and catch things so no small critters or cats for me please.  

I will be fine with respectful older children but prefer not to live with small kids as they make me nervous.

I will need a patient family who will allow me to settle in at my own pace. I also don’t appreciate being smothered, poked or prodded by people I don’t know; that’s just not my thing.

I have had quite a bit of training and will make a wonderful companion for someone who likes fun activities.

This is a courtesy post. I’ll be waiting with my family in Santa Rosa.

https://www.bayareagsr.org/available-dogs/1440-sarah-cp


IF YOU ARE interested in SARAH, Please go to the webpage above and contact us directly using the forms there.


Find us on Facebook : https://www.facebook.com/Bay-Area-German-Shepherd-Rescue-184324951742737/

Bay Area German Shepherd Rescue normally has 20 dogs all over the Bay Area. You can see more of our available dogs on the right hand side of this page.

Nina is a senior dog looking for a forever home. She is human friendly and said to be dog friendly by the sending shelter. Potty training and crate training unknown.

UPDATE: Nina is a super sweet, American pit bull mix who is 8 years old. Nina came to TAPS in mid-December from PAWS and is quiet, friendly and 61 pounds of pure sweetness! Although Nina arrived at PAWS as a stray, it is apparent that Nina is familiar with car rides and a home. In my car, Nina simply rode quietly and if she was not sleeping, she was quietly looking out the window. In my home, she was surprisingly active for her age and did not want to nap because she wanted to soak in all the attention she could possibly get in her short outing away from the shelter. Nina was not interested in ropes or bones (but she recently had dental work), yet she had fun destroying a stuffed dog toy. She also does not like hardwood floors and at times, appeared to walk gingerly which leads me to believe that she may be showing signs of the onset of arthritis. Nina preferred to stay on the carpet areas of my home and, although I coaxed her onto my couch, it was apparent that being on furniture is not something she is comfortable doing. Overall, Nina is an incredibly happy, loving dog who simply wants to lay on your carpeted floor, be petted and is extremely treat motivated. Unfortunately, Nina has no background information, so her potty training and crate training is an unknown, but outside of one accident in my house, she does seem familiar with going outside to potty. PAWS also reports that she is dog friendly so if you are looking for a loving, calm, sweet middle-aged dog, then Nina will be perfect!

animal.description:
(Nashville, TN) Supra is ready for his "Foster to Adopt" home. Supra is 5 years old and was diagnosed with Discospondylitis in October that caused him to be paralyzed in his back end. This was caused by pure neglect. After medication and therapy he is now able to walk, even run. However, he still requires medication every 8 hours due to the intensity of the infection in his back. Supra is also on a slow kill HW method as he can't have the immiticide injections. He has his follow up with UTK on Feb 19th and should be released in regards to his Discospondylitis! He is doing AMAZING! He is also neutered and vaccinations and preventatives are UTD. 

All food and medical, including supplements and preventatives, will be paid by the rescue until he is 100% at which point adoption will take place. We would like him to settle down with his forever family as soon as possible as the longer they are with their foster, the harder the transition. We just simply will not finalize adoption until he is 100% with his Discospondylitis and HW Negative. 

Supra is the the most LOVING boy you will ever meet! His tail wags with so much appreciation at times I think he is going to take off like a helicopter. Supra has been inro'ed to dogs on leashes ONLY and done very well. Both dogs he met were low energy, very balanced with excellent social skills. Supra wouldn't do well with a high energy dog. He will need to go to a home with a small or medium dog with fair energy due to the sensitivity of his back (or no dogs; NOT because of behavior but due to his back). Supra LOVES car rides, walks, toys and especially chin scratches. This boy LOVES life regardless of what he has gone through. I've never had a happier foster in my home despite what he has suffered. 

He will need a home with mostly carpet to avoid the slip and sliding. I've had to place rugs on the wood and tile floor to help him. I know this is a lot to take on for an adoptive animal but the love you will get in return is multiplied by infinity. He just wants a human to love and be with; he needs to be with his human. And these medical issues will not be forever! Please give him a chance to love you! 

If you are interested in adopting Supra, please visit our website for the FAQs and application. If you do not meet requirements your application will not be processed. Website link below:

https://www.battleforthebully.org/

animal.description:
Hi I'm Kimber. I was found left alone with my brother and sister in a house. I'm a somewhat shy and cautious girl, but can you blame me? I am looking for a home with people who will be kind and patient with me while I come out of my shell and get used to my surroundings. I also get along well with other dogs, so having a furry sibling would be amazing. Once I'm comfortable in my home, I'm sure to blossom and be a perfect companion.

From my foster family: I love squeaky toys, treats, tummy rubs, and long walks. I may be a bit shy at first, but once you have my trust, I will be a loyal companion. I have learned to sit, lie down, and how to go into my crate, where I now sleep all night. I love to sniff but am not a chewer, jumper or destructive. I have lived with other dogs previously and now get very excited seeing dogs on walks. My foster family is working with me on this. Ideally, I would love someone to exercise with, but a couple walks a day and playtime will suffice. Despite my size, I am quite gentle and a good walker (unless I see a dog friend). I am attentive, affectionate, and playful, but also love just to relax in a comfy spot. I promise I will do my best to make you happy and always greet you with a wagging tail and huge grin. Will you help me find my forever home?
animal.name: Kimber

animal.description:
Venus is a 3 year old Black Mouth Cur mix that was on the euthanasia list in an overcrowded Tulsa shelter. She is a playful and silly girl who thinks she is a lap dog. She knows commands such as sit, down and shake. She is not distructive and seldom barks. Although she is slow to warm up to men, Venus is super sweet and loves to give kisses. Venus LOVES water and will happily get in the shower with you unless there is a barrier. Venus gave birth to 9 puppies on 1/10/21 and won't be available until she is finished raising her puppies. We are, however, accepting applications for pre-approval.

The suggested adoption donation for Venus is $350. We are a 501c3 organization which means that your donation may be TAX DEDUCTIBLE. Your donation goes toward the high cost of veterinary care for our animals in rescue, as well as providing supportive services to animals in homes.

Information about the adoption process: All adoptions require a completed ADOPTION APPLICATION. Once your application is approved, we will put you in touch with the dogs foster to see if you and the pet are a good match. If so, we will arrange a meeting for you and the pet. The adoptions for all of our animals will take place in the Omaha, NE area and must be done by the adoptive family in person. We do not ship or deliver.

Please Note: We are a RESCUE, which is different from a shelter. We conduct veterinary and personal reference checks during the application approval process. We always select the right applicant for each dog, based on the dogs needs. If you and the dog are not a good match, we will help you select another dog, or we will keep your approved application on file for 6 months.

To learn about Muddy Paws Second Chance Rescue or donate to our animals, please visit our website at MuddyPawsSecondChanceRescue.com or our Facebook Page.

animal.description:
***AVAILABLE FOR ADOPTION AT OUR FLORIDA LOCATION***

Miley is a female Black Mouth Cur mix. She is approximately 4 years old and weighs around 60 lbs. 

From her foster home:  Miley is a calm sweet girl that loves to snooze on the couch. She is a bit shy as she is getting acclimated to her new surroundings. She is fully house trained and has good manners. She has a medium energy level.

When allowed time and patience, she comes out of her shell. She loves to play, tug, and wrestle, but sometimes doesn't realize how big her paws are that she swings around. 

She is good with kids. She is good with other dogs, but has shown a strong prey drive towards small animals. She is not a good match for homes with cats, chickens, rabbits, or other small animals. 

Miley strongly dislikes loud noises such as gun shots and fireworks 
She has overcome her previous fear of thunder. 
Her adopter will probably need to pursue calming methods/products to manage her noise anxiety if and when needed. 

She travels well in a car. She responds to commands such as off, up, leave it and load up (into truck) as well as other verbal cues. She has been working on leash training. 

Miley, like so many of our adults and mommas that come in, is heartworm positive. This is NOT contagious and is not a death sentence! We have started her on Heartgard which will keep new worms from growing and allow the ones already present to die off slowly. This is the safest way to do it in the group home setting.  It is a very manageable treatment plan. Included in her adoption is a year supply of Heartgard. 

Miley is available in Bonifay, Florida through the rescue efforts of The Lucky Puppy Rescue. The minimum $250 adoption fee includes spay/neuter surgery, vaccinations, de-worm, flea prevention, heartworm prevention and martingale safety collar.   Adoption fee payment methods accepted are credit, debit, Paypal and bank checks. No personal checks or cash. Applications must be submitted through our website - theluckypuppy.org - thank you! You may copy and paste the following link to apply: http://www.theluckypuppy.org/adoption-application.

animal.description:
So sweet!Buster was born around December 12, 2013, and weighs about 15 pounds. Somehow Buster found himself sitting in a high kill shelter in Kentucky. The shelter reached out to us knowing we have a soft spot for older dogs and Joyful happily agreed to bring him to safety. Buster rode well in the car and does fine with the other dogs however he can be rather bossy. (Update: He can be around other dogs just fine, but needs to live as an only dog as he will protect his human from other dogs - great with people!) He was around older children and did fine. He is a happy go lucky type and not nippy with us at all. Buster walks nicely on a leash and is ready to find his forever home!
The Adoption Fee for this dog is $350.00 Adoptions fees vary based on adoptability. In general, our fees include spay/neuter, all age-appropriate vaccines, Home Again microchipping & registration, worming & flea control - a 'complete' pet. We accept CASH or Visa/Mastercard ONLY. Joyful Rescues has no funding except for our adoption fees and miscellaneous donations. Pet care and vet bills are expensive - you must be ready to take on this financial (as well as emotional) responsibility. YOU MUST BE AT LEAST 25 YEARS OF AGE TO ADOPT A DOG FROM JOYFUL RESCUES We keep our pet list as up-to-date as possible. As soon as a pet is adopted, it is removed from the list. If a pet is still showing, it is still available for adoption. Can't Adopt Me? SPONSOR ME Look for the Link 'Special Instructions to Seller' if you want to note a particular pet
Before you seek to adopt a pet from Joyful Rescues, please read our Pet Adoption page http://www.joyfulrescues.org/pet_adoption.html.

animal.description:
Maui arrived from a family that couldn't take care of her properly.  She's enjoying time with her boxer friends and the cats in her foster home.

With a guesstimated birthday in July 2020, Maui weighs about 30 lb.  We've included a picture of her sharing a meal with one of the boxers to give an idea of her size right now.

Maui is affectionate and ready to play.  She's comfy in a 42" crate and does well on a leash with some pulling.  Her house-training is going well when kept on a regular schedule of every hour to reinforce waiting.

April 2020:  We are not holding public adoption events at this time.  Qualified families are being invited to appointments to meet specific dogs.  There are currently no opportunities to view multiple dogs and adoption events aren't being held at Tractor Supply in Lenoir.

Whether dogs / puppies come in as strays or owner surrenders, we usually have to make our best guess as to birthdate and breed.   

If adopted into a home with other animals, particularly cats, your new pet should be crated or secured when you're not available to supervise to insure a harmonious relationship.  

A vet reference is required to confirm responsible pet ownership.  We suggest first time pet owners look for an adult dog for companionship and to gain experience through another rescue or your local government-run animal control..

Adoption fee covers two vaccinations plus spay / neuter if using our local low-cost spay/neuter clinic (overnight stay required) and surgery occurs as agreed upon in the adoption contract.  Convenience fee equal to refundable spay/neuter deposit may be added if using our veterinarian.  Additional fees for 3rd puppy vaccination, refundable spay/neuter deposit, etc. may apply.  

We are an all-volunteer, foster-based rescue.  We receive no funding from agencies.  Available animals can be seen most Saturdays at Tractor Supply in Lenoir from 10:00 a.m. to 2:00 p.m.  We recommend interested parties contact us to pre-qualify for adoption so their new furry family can go home once paperwork is complete.  Fees are required in cash.  For more information on our organization, our website is www.petpartnersrescue.org.

animal.description:
Meet Rhonda! Rhonda is a healthy Boxer girl who is about 8 years old and weighs around 45lbs. Sadly, her previous family left her behind when they moved away, and she was left to fend for herself for a few weeks before she was found. She was very thin, too weak to walk, and had a leg injury as well as an eye infection. She has recovered nicely, but considering this recent experience and her age, Rhonda may not be a type of dog that goes on long hikes on weekends. She is affectionate and loves giving hugs to her humans, and more than anything, she misses being part of a family. Rhonda gets along with other dogs, but young rambunctious ones are too much for her, so a mellow dog would be a better sibling for her than a puppy or a high energy dog. She cannot live peacefully with cats. She walks well on leash, and knows some commands like “sit”, and “paw” in Spanish. She hopes that her next companion will be as faithful as she is, and she can live out her golden years with them. Rhonda was rescued from Becerias, Mexico, and is being fostered in Bend, OR. Will you be her hero?
If you are interested in Rhonda, please fill out an application at www.streetdoghero.org/forms

animal.description:
Meet Eveey! Our educated guess is that she is a Pit Bull mix, approximately two years old and about 55 pounds.

This independent lady is not a velcro dog by any means. She's very affectionate and loves snuggles and cuddles, but knows when she's ready for some "me time" in her own space.

She's a quick study, excited to learn new things and very obedient. Eveey does really well on a leash and is a great running partner, and can easily do 5 miles at a medium pace run with no issues.

Eveey prides herself as the sole provider of love, companionship, and joy to you. She can get very assertive when she encounters cats, squirrels, or other dogs and needs time to calm down.

For that reason, she's looking for an experienced family who's willing to help her with training, and her fosters report that she's making good progress already. Eveey would do best as the only dog in the home, and with older children.
