animal.description:
Meet Autumn! Our best guess is that this sweet girl is a Plott Hound mix and approximately 4-5 years old.

Autumn is a sweet, fun-loving, energetic girl! She does really well with positive reinforcement and loves treats. After a good walk, her favorite thing to do is cuddle up next to you on the couch with all the blankets you can find. She's a good listener, loves people, and prefers to be an only child as while she loves to play with her fellow dogs, she doesn't really like it when they hang around too often. She doesn't bark at the door, but she will love any guest that comes in -- and she's sure to show it with plenty of kisses and tail wags. Her favorite place to be pet is on her head and under her chin.

While she has no problem being a lazy, indoor dog, she's an outside girl at heart as her real passion is getting out her amazing energy with a good run, swim, or walk. She is 100% crate trained, potty trained, and knows all of her basic commands (sit, stay, wait, take, down, heel, & come) without needing treats. She loves to play and is excellent at tug-of-war and fetch (both on land and in the water). She has an abundant amount of energy that is easily expelled through walks and play time.

Autumn should go to a home with no other dogs so that she can be the queen of the castle! Autumn would also do best in a single family home or townhouse outside of the city.

animal.description:
***AVAILABLE FOR ADOPTION AT OUR FLORIDA LOCATION***

Lulu is a 2 year old female Hound/Shepherd mix. She weighs approximately 40 lbs. From her foster home:  Lulu can be timid and submissive at first but give her time to open up and she is the sweetest dog.  After some patience and time, she loves to snuggle on the couch or your lap. She is good with kids. She is wary of men. 

Lulu is house trained and has started crate training. She is very well mannered. She has mastered commands such as sit, down, leave it, up, off and load up in addition to verbal cues. 

She has a medium/high energy level and LOVES to run and chase sticks and balls. She fetches well inside the house and knows the command to drop it. Outdoors, she is learning to return the ball/stick. She loves playing with other dogs and listens so well that her foster parents let her play off leash outside, though she walks great on a leash. She also travels well in a vehicle. 

Lulu, like so many of our adults and mommas that come in, is heartworm positive. This is NOT contagious and is not a death sentence! We have started her on Heartgard which will keep new worms from growing and allow the ones already present to die off slowly. This is the safest way to do it in the group home setting.  It is a very manageable treatment plan. Included in her adoption is a year supply of Heartgard. 

She gave birth and raised her puppies at our rescue and now it is her time to be a cherished pet as well. 

Lulu is available in Bonifay, Florida through the rescue efforts of The Lucky Puppy Rescue. The minimum $250 adoption fee includes spay/neuter surgery, vaccinations, de-worm, flea prevention, heartworm prevention and martingale safety collar. Adoption fee payment methods accepted are credit, debit, Paypal and bank checks. No personal checks or cash. Applications must be submitted through our website - theluckypuppy.org - thank you! You may copy and paste the following link to apply: http://www.theluckypuppy.org/adoption-application.

Sometimes the pets appear to be a particular breed(s) in the pictures we receive from our rescue partners and when they arrive we are surprised to see an entirely different breed(s) in person! If you choose to DNA test your adopted pet, test results may vary from company to company and our breed guess may not be reflected in those results as it is just that, our best guess. It is with deep longing that we wish there was a breed called "cute" as we believe all of our dogs would fall under this new breed classification!

animal.description: Johnny is a 2-3 year old Pit Bull mix. He is loose and wiggly. He likes to give gentle kisses. Johnny is mellow most of the time but will have bursts of energy. (medium) He doesn't know how to walk on a leash but with a little coaxing and basic obedience training, this could easily be resolved. He is not food motivated and does not know any commands. He is willing to learn tho! He is afraid of cats in a shelter environment. We recommend children 8 years and up due to his anxiety level. Dogs are generally tested with dogs of their own size; and dog meets with the resident dogs are always encouraged. Our cat test should be used as a general purpose screening only to rule out overt aggression; we always recommend caution when introducing dogs to cats in the home. Recommendation on suitability of placement with children by their ages is based on behavioral observations including energy level and response to body handling. We never recommend leaving young children unsupervised with dogs, and we cannot guarantee the behavior of dogs with children, other pets or cats. Behavior evaluations should be considered as a snapshot of the behavior of the dog at this point in time; JHS believes all dog families need to be prepared to invest time and energy into training as well as provide common sense management of their new dog. We always encourage family to do some research on the breeds or mixes of breeds prior to adoption as many can have some unique characteristics that may or may not fit into their families. Always remember that the majority of dogs at our shelter have been exposed to or may have kennel cough. Kennel cough is contagious to other dogs, please talk to your vet if you have any questions about kennel cough prior to adoption. Please ask your adoption counselor at time of adoption if you have any unanswered questions regarding illnesses and treatments of the path that you are adopting. For more information about this dog or any others at our Shelter, please visit www.joplinhumane.org. We are the Joplin Humane Society in Joplin, Missouri. 417-623-3642 I AM SPONSORED! animal.description:
MEET CHET!!

I was given the name Chet at the shelter, but my foster family has been calling me Blue. I enjoy being with you all of the time being touched and played with. I am learning to not bark if I am not being attended, but this is a slow process. Additionally, I am learning how to be gentle all of the time when I am playing. I enjoy being mouthy. However, I accidentally broke my teeth while in the shelter. So, if I accidentally play too hard it rarely results in my person being hurt. I respond well to redirection with a bone or a pull toy. Since my teeth are sensitive I do not particulate like hard ropes to tug with. But I do enjoy a nice soft rope. I will play fetch intermittently, but do love chasing and chewing on a nice squeaky ball. I have been living with another dog. There have been no issues. A few growls here and there but I immediately stop when told to. I have met a cat a few times. I am generally respectful. I did try and chase once but not only stopped but laid down immediately when told to stop. I understand basic commands but it some times takes me a few seconds to respond. I love meeting new people. When I meet other dogs it is best if I go on a walk with them until I calm down. After that, I get along just fine. I am crate trained and split time between sleeping in my crate and a bed. When I am in my crate over night I do not cry and cuddle nicely in bed when I am allowed. The only time I bark in my crate is if I am in time out in it and see that you are there ignoring me. I do need to have my meals portioned out. I will continue eating until the food is gone. I still have a little more weight to gain for my spine to be covered but am getting there quickly. I really do love people and hope that I can find a forever home in which I will be played with and cuddled every day.

If you are interested in meeting Chet, please visit our website for our online application www.underdogaz.com

Also, please know that the breed mix listed is simply a guess. In most cases, we don’t know their background. We encourage you to base your decision on individual personality and pet qualities instead of relying on our guess.

Please understand, we only adopt our animals out near the Chicagoland area. Questions? Email us at adoptions@sccrescue.org. Hope to see you become part of the SCCR family!

You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Update: Cletus is 9 years old now. Because of family circumstances, Cletus is coming back to the rescue. While he was with his family he learned to get along with cats and was buddies with the other dog there. He loved the two kids in his family too. Cletus is looking for an active family to be part of. He still needs some work on his manners, like not helping himself to things on the counter or in the trash, but will reward you with lots of love and laughs at his coon hound antics. Even though he is 9 yrs old, he still has lots of energy and will need daily walks.
Hello my name is Cletus. Everyone tells me just what a good looking fella I am. I was found as a stray and ended up at the dog pound. No one came to claim me. I am a happy energetic guy, good with other dogs and people. I could use a little work on my manners because I become bored easily and just try to find things to do. I also see cats as fun things to chase so shouldn't go to a home with a kitty. I am house trained, up to date with vaccines, neutered, and heartworm negative. If you are a hound lover, well here I am, just waiting for you. If you would like to meet me, please fill out an application below. We will make a date! Love Cletus

animal.description:
Buddy! This handsome boy is a 4 year old pit mix and about 60 pounds. He is house trained and crate trained. Buddy is dog friendly, cat friendly and kid friendly, but would love to find a quiet forever home where he can enjoy a life of leisure and relax by himself.

While Buddy is heartworm positive, this can easily be managed with medication.

Buddy's personality has really started to shine! He adores belly rubs and going outside to sniff and explore. If you show him love, he will follow you around like a shadow. He lets you pick him up, rub his face, lift his paws, and even wrestle. He's been great company while working from home and is clumsy when he gets excited which is extremely cute. Even though he had a rough past, somehow he still trusts and loves people.

He would be a great addition to any family willing to give him the second chance he deserves. It doesn't get much better than his temperament!

Apply online at petrescuealliance.com to give this boy a loving home!

If you are interested in adding this pup to your family, please submit an application at www.petrescuealliance.com. All questions will be answered and meet and greets set up following a review of application. If the dog is listed on our website or Petfinder, they are still available! Pet Rescue Alliance does our best to provide accurate information about the dogs we have available for adoption. We cannot make any guarantees about age, breed or temperament.

Paw Up! Date: Kringle aka Hans Had Surgery Today!!

Our sweet boy out of the Ramona Humane Society had his surgery today and it went very well. Kringle had to have a plate put into secure his pelvis and and Femoral Head Ostectomy to make sure he will be able to walk again. The surgeon and his treating Dr. at @Camino Veterinary Hospital in Irvine were very pleased with the outcome. Kringle is resting comfortably and will be ready to head to a foster home in a day or so. Kringle is such a love, everyone who meets him adores him. We are grateful we were able to help him. If you would like to donate towards his medical care, we are still about $2k short, you can do so in the following ways:

Facebook: Via the button on the post

labradorsandfriends.org

friends.org

Tax ID# 32-0195297

Thank you everyone for your support!! If you are interested in fostering or eventually adopting Kringle please fill out our online application at
www.labradorsandfriends.org

Previously:

URGENT: KRINGLE NEEDS OUR HELP!!

A few days before Christmas a sweet, young shepherd mix, found himself at the Ramona Humane Society after having been hit by a car. He was taking to CVS for immediate medical care/stabilization and x-rays showing a bad pelvic break. Sadly, he then spent the holiday at the shelter. Kringle, who was also known as Hans, couldn't stand, wasn't eating, but had to complete his stray hold, which was up Saturday. At 9 am we were told there was ZERO rescue interest in helping him. We just couldn't let him sit there any longer, we knew from the x-rays that his break was surgical, but 6 days was long enough to wait. We immediately put a plan in place to get him out and to our vet. Kringle will need surgery, a plate to hold his pelvis together so his leg can be stabilized. Kringle is so sweet and thankfully, there wasn't any damage to his spinal cord or femoral head. The bad news is we are looking at a $4,000 surgery. Please consider making a 100% Tax Deductible Donation towards his surgery and medical care.

animal.description:
Tilly was born on a property south of San Antonio. She was not socialized with people at all so it takes her some time to come around. She is very, very sweet and would do best in a home with other dogs. We would prefer a home with older kids just because screaming may scare her. 

She is 7-8 months old, good with dogs and will most likely be okay with cats and  kids.  She is potty trained, kenneled trained but is still working on walking on a leash. That has been one thing that is taking her the most time to get used to because she is scared to go on walks or have the leash attached. An adopter needs to be aware that she is not going to be comfortable walking on leash or being loaded into a car right away. An adopter will need to consider a mobile vet or further training to help her adjust and overcome her fear.

*Because she missed her critical socialization period, it is safe to say that she will carry anxiety with her. So she may not be the dog that you take to the park or lake as she may get overwhelmed. Owners will need to be patient and continue to work on coping skills and calming skills so she can have confidence in new situations.

Tilly will need to go to a home with playful dogs. She functions best on a routine, and needs to be kenneled at night to avoid chewing. 

Tilly has a $100 adoption fee and interested parties must complete an adoption application via www.pawsa.org under the adoptables tab. Her foster is happy to schedule meet and greets.

Again, She is very, very sweet and would do best in a home with other playful dogs.

What a transformation this boy has made. We knew he was going to be a beauty but had no idea he would turn out this stunning with a personality to match. He is such a good dog, we can't say enough good things about him. He is well rounded, sweet, playful and gets along with everyone. This boy just wants love and comfort from here on out. 

His progress from a bleeding, scratchy, uncomfortable dog to a fully feathered out beauty, really puts a lump in your throat and a skip in your step and makes you want to yell at the top of your lungs "WE DID IT!!

Goliath is recovering from his early days of neglect. He is getting more playful everyday; he tries to keep up with the other dogs and is learning how to play and have fun. We call him the gentle giant. He is a good boy and is looking for a home to learn all the comforts and good things for boys like him. Goliath relies on other confident dogs to help bring him out of his shell so we are looking for a home with another confident dog for this big boy. He gets along great with female dogs and most likely would do well with a male but would need proper intros.

This poor boy had been living under a house for months with no care. His face was swollen so much he could not open his eyes. His fur was missing. He needed help.

We had the neighbors set a trap and after 3 weeks they trapped him and we brought him straight to the ER.

animal.description:
Hello, my name is Pike (but you can call me anything you like since I can't hear you).  I'm a handsome 2.5 year old boy weighing in at around 70 lbs.  I'm obviously a mix of all the most handsome breeds around.  Not only am I sweet and loving, my mom thinks that I am the smartest boy around.  I'm deaf so I communicate with sign language and already know commands for sit, down, come, potty, no and most importantly, good boy.  If you give me a thumbs-up, I know I've been good and give the biggest smile around!  I have picked up on my signs so quickly and will easily learn more (stay gives me trouble because of my wiggly butt).  I love to snuggle and be with my people but I also love to run in the yard and chase the ball and squirrels.  I'm looking for a calm home with someone who will be patient when things get scary and give me all the love and belly rubs I can get.  Tiny humans can be unpredictable and they make me nervous so I need a home without them.  I do well with cats and have done well with dogs in the past.  My adoption fee is $250.00.

To adopt this pet, please visit https://www.louieslegacy.org/adopt

All of our dogs come spayed or neutered, fully up to date on vaccinations, including rabies (if age appropriate) and bordetella, are microchipped, heartworm negative, current on flea/tick and heartworm prevention, dewormed, and treated for any ailments found upon veterinary examination. The adoption fee covers a portion of these services, and makes it possible for us to continue rescuing animals.  

For more information on the adoption fees and the adoption process, please complete our adoption application here: https://www.louieslegacy.org/adopt - an application allows us to get to know your family better so we can assess whether the animal you are interested in is a good match for your home. An application does not obligate you to adopt. Please understand that due to the volume of applications some animals receive, we are unable to contact all applicants. If your application is considered a good fit for the dog you are interested in, or even a different pet, a volunteer will give you a call as soon as possible.  

We are a foster based rescue and do not have a shelter location where dogs can be seen during the week. Please see our Facebook page at https://www.facebook.com/LouiesLegacy for our weekly adoption album if you are interested in meeting a dog in person. Not all animals attend every adoption event, please check our Facebook page for animal event times and locations before you make a trip to meet a specific animal.

Thanks so much for caring about a needy animal!

animal.description:
Updated: 1/21/2021
Hello, I'm Hildy and I am looking for a family who loves light blue eyes and very soft fur. I am approximately 18 months and weigh 40 pounds. With my breed mix, I am full of life with lots of spunk and high energy and need lots of room to run and play! A home with lots of yard to run in and perhaps a fence would be ideal. I am not the kind of doggy that would do well in an apartment, as it is too confined. I would be great with a family that loves outdoor activities such as running and hiking. I am early on in my training for leash walking, so I am still pulling on my leash.
I obey a few commands and am learning a few more, but need a patient owner as I am young and still pushing limits. I am house-broken and crate-trained. I take treats nicely, but am still learning to eat slowly and calmly, especially when other dogs are with me eating in the same room. I did well when they gave me a bath even though it wasn't one of my favorite things to do. I love to play with all sorts of toys-from soft cuddly ones to semi-hard rubbery ones to hard bones. I will bring all of them to you so that you can play with me. I also like to play 'ring around the island'/peek-a-boo. When introduced to other dogs, a slow introduction is best. I like to play with other dogs, but I get very excited when playing and I am quite intense and need continued direction on proper play etiquette. The other dogs don't understand that I just want to have fun. So, I will require continued training on learning to respect boundaries. I like kids and have been around ones as young as two years old, but I should always be supervised with littles as I rough house when playing and don't wish to knock them down. I will occasionally watch tv when something on it intrigues me. I enjoy looking out the window in search of squirrels and bunnies.
I am the best doggy if you allow me plenty of exercise including walks and the chance to run several times daily. If you are interested in a finding a friendly, fun loving, and energetic girl, look no further. Hope to meet you soon!
Adoption Fee: $475.00
We are a Wisconsin state licensed dog rescue -WI# 402433

***We do not have a central adoption center at this time. All our dogs are in private foster homes within WI. At this time we only place our dogs in areas of WI. The breed of our dogs is our best guess with the help of our veterinarians.
Our Weight Classes are as follows:
0- 25lbs - Small
26- 45lbs - Medium
46-89 - Large
90+ X-large
If you are adopting an adult dog, which we consider 6 months of age or older, your adoption fee includes the following:
Spay/Neuter, Rabies and Distemper shots, dewormed, flea & tick preventative, heartworm tested and microchipped.
If you are adopting a dog younger than 6 months of age, the dog will be up to date on the shots as per the dogs age. The dog will be dewormed, flea/tick preventative and microchipped. We only spay/neuter our dogs by 6 months of age. If you decide to adopt a younger dog than 6 months of age, they will need to be spayed/neutered at one of our preferred clinics. This will be determined by your contract along with the month they should have their surgery. This is included in your adoption fee.
Once you are approved with our rescue, you can meet any one of our dogs within the fosters home. If you are interested in the dog you met, you can take the dog home under our mandatory foster to adopt program. You receive 5 days to see if the dog is the right fit for your home.
If it is, we will conduct the home visit and finalize adoption. If it is not, it is returned to the foster. We are happy to find you another dog that meets your needs in your home.
If a dog is listed as PENDING, a family has met the dog and planning on adopting the dog after the home visit has been conducted. We always suggest sending in an application for a dog because there are times where the dogs are given back to us under the foster to adopt program. There are many reasons dogs are returned but normally it just was not the right fit for all.Please go to WWW.TAILWAGGERS911.COM under HOW TO ADOPT . We have an online application that is very easy to fill out.

animal.description:
Levi is a gorgeous, intelligent silver pittie mix who is 2 years old and weighs 50 lbs.  He is a happy, playful, social boy who loves other dogs, loves every person he meets, loves car rides, and has good leash manners.  He was picked up as an emaciated stray in Barrow County with a broken leg after being hit by a car.  Sadly he sat at the shelter for 2 weeks until BarkVille heard about him, arranged to have him treated by our partner vet, and placed him in a wonderful foster home where he has been putting on weight & regaining his health daily.  He is on crate restrictions right now as his leg continues to heal, but his foster mom describes him as a fun, loving, medium energy boy who loves to run and would thrive in a home with a fenced yard, possibly another a dog or 2, and some kids that he can call his own.  Levi is housebroken, crate trained, neutered, fully vaccinated & microchipped.  

For more information about Levi, please email us at info@barkvilledogrescue.org. If you would like to adopt this sweet boy, please submit an application for him at https://www.barkvilledogrescue.org/applications

animal.description:
Wanted: an angel to provide TLC and snuggles to a very lovable senior dog.
 
Chico is a 10 pound, 15-year-old Pomeranian mix who has been through a lot recently--owner surrender, the loss of his sister, and some dental surgery that resulted in a significantly less toothy grin. Despite it all, Chico continues to stay upbeat and love life.  
 
Chico is completely house-trained but does occasionally experience some fecal incontinence overnight. He is super well-behaved and chill with no need for a crate. He sleeps in his own bed next to his foster’s bed at night and just about anywhere warm and snuggly during the day. Chico doesn’t chew or bark and is largely uninterested in toys. He’s just a wonderful happy little companion.
 
Due to Chico’s age, he will need to go to a special home where he can get the support and care required for a senior dog. Chico can handle short walks or being let out in the yard, but his mobility is limited by his arthritis, for which he will need medication long term. This also means he’ll need support and supervision when he goes out to do his business. Ideally his new home will have someone home most of the time and won’t have very young or hyper two- or four-legged friends. He will need arthritis medication.
 
Chico is looking forward to living in the lap of love and luxury for his golden days. He adores affection and is the perfect lap buddy. Can you be Chico’s guardian angel?

Interested in adopting this dog? Visit our website (http://www.SecondCityCanineRescue.org) to fill out an application and to find out where this dog may be shown this weekend.

We love our dogs. We want happy lives for all of them and are looking for the home that provides the best fit for each dog’s individual needs. Please understand that there may be multiple families interested in this dog. Come to the show to find out if this dog is the right fit for you — it's helpful to bring all family members and current dogs. 

Also, please know that the breed mix listed is simply a guess. In most cases, we don’t know their background. We encourage you to base your decision on individual personality and pet qualities instead of relying on our guess.

Please understand, we only adopt our animals out near the Chicagoland area. Questions? Email us at adoptions@sccrescue.org. Hope to see you become part of the SCCR family!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.wagoninn.rescuegroups.org
Lexi is a beautiful hound mix who was found in a rural shelter in Kansas by one of our rescue partners. She liked Lexi and her dog-mate Lucky so much that she brought them back home to Louisiana so they could head up to Wag On Inn Rescue.
Lexi is a sweet senior 9-year-old girl who sometimes acts half her age. She loves to be around people who supply her with pets, ear scratches, and tummy rubs. A pleasure to foster, Lexi quickly adapted well to her foster home and is fun to be around. She loves squishy toys and the tennis ball, and is just a happy-go-lucky pup. This good girl does not counter-surf (although she can due to her height), does not get into trash, or chew or destroy anything in the house. She also is housetrained. She has 24/7 run of the house and has not been crated. She does tend to pull on a leash at first and then relaxes. She LOVES her walks!
Lexi is adventurous, and her foster parents would not trust her off leash unless in a fenced area. She is not adept at coming back when called. She is smart, though, and loving towards her people, and she is also treat-motivated, so her family can work on training. She is an escape artist too, so her family should work on "wait" with her.
Lexi is super sweet and will be your constant companion. She LOVES car rides. She could be fine as an only dog or with male canine companions but no small dogs. No cats for Lexi.
Lexi had very itchy skin upon arriving in NJ and her foster mom is working on this with an antihistamine, gentle baths, and a special grain free diet. Miss Lexi will be a wonderful companion to her new family.
Lexi is fully vetted - spayed, up to date on vaccines and microchipped. She is heartworm negative. Lexi's adoption fee is $300.

How to Adopt Me!
If you are interested in learning more about me, and possibly making me part of your family, please go to wagoninn.rescuegroups.org . Click on the orange Online Adoption Application button to fill out an application. A Wag On Inn volunteer will be in touch soon!

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Name: Greta
DOB: 10/15/15

Weight: 69 lbs

- Potty trained
- Has all basic training; sit, knows name, lay down, shake, etc
- Loves kids and people
- Is vocal, likes to howl, bark, and coo
- Does NOT do well in kennel but is trustworthy outside of kennel
- Would do best with fenced in yard
- Would do best as only animal in home

Did those big brown eyes draw you in? Was it the goofy floppy ears? Maybe you saw the picture of her cuddling with a cat and thought man.. Greta could be my dog! She could be the one! Please read this little paragraph before applying. This old girl is looking for her forever family, not someone who loves just her cute very smushable face.

Greta found herself homeless after getting into a dispute with a neighbor dog a few months back and is on the lookout for a family who is willing to let her be the center of attention. Greta can be defensive around other animals so she would be best as an only pet in the home.

Greta loves people, toys, treats, and playing ball. Her favorite activities include cuddling, napping, chasing balls, and playing with her stuffy toys. She walks okay on a leash but does tend to pull as she is a hound mix who is lead by her nose. A fenced in yard to play and romp in would be perfect for her!

She is not an overly active girl, she also has very good house manners assuming there is nothing tasty she can reach on your counters. She tells you when she needs to go outside along with chatting about daily events, the weather, and her overall mood. Greta is a hound mix, she tends to be vocal and loves to talk to you about all manner of affairs.

This amazing, sweet, soft adorable old gal has been let down by folks too many times have anyone else not love her with their whole hearts. When applying for Greta, please read the bullets and info above and understand that she is truly looking for a retirement home to settle down in and be comfortable with.

Her foster parents love her very much and want what's best for her but after having her returned twice due to folks feeling as though she is "too much dog", we feel it is important to be transparent in her needs. If you don't plan to let her sleep in bed with you, steal your blankets, share your snacks with her, and get hound hair all over your clothes, this gal isn't for you.

An adoption application is the best way to show your interest in an animal. Please check out our website, www.ruffstartrescue.org for more details and additional pictures on any of our animals! All Ruff Start dogs and cats are spayed/neutered, up to date on age appropriate vaccines, microchipped, dewormed, and on monthly flea/tick and heartworm prevention (dogs) as well as heartworm tested (dogs). Ruff Start Rescue is a foster based rescue. Animals are located in homes throughout Minnesota. We do not have a facility where animals are kept. Ruff Start Rescue Adoption Policies: http://www.ruffstartrescue.org/info/display?PageID=11744

animal.description:
'U' Litter 2020Updated: 2/1/2021
Litter Name: 'U' Litter 2020
Born: 11/12/2020
My name is Uzo - I am a female boxer mix pup and I weigh around 12 pounds. You can see in my pictures that I am a sweet little girl.
I am single and ready to mingle! Well.. I still have some of my litter mates but looking for my own furever family that is!
My name may be different, but it means "the road is good" and I know that I am one lucky puppy and the road I am on to find my furever family is a great one for sure.
Likes: Being around my family, food, snuggles, kisses, toys to chew on, and all that fun cute puppy stuff.
Dislikes: Not having food, shelters, no loving home and being cold. Baths aren't my favorite hobby either but I know I need to stay fresh and clean for those snuggles!
Seeking: Family to love me forever, keep me warm and fed. Long walks and possible doggie parks in the future - my older foster brothers say it's a lot of fun. I am very well socialized with humans and other dogs.
My furever family will need to continue to work on my training since I am so young. When I play with other dogs I can be very vocal and hold my own even with dogs much bigger than me. With submissive dogs I can get a little carried away when I play but can take direction from other dogs and humans when given the command to calm down.
I have started giving cues to go outside to do my business but still have a few accidents here and there.
Being with my foster family has been awesome. I know I am loved and well cared for as I wait patiently. There are 3 little girls here too that just love me to pieces. I have 2 furry older foster brothers that I really enjoy playing with. There are cats here, and I just try to play with them but they don't really like dogs so they stay away.
I have a lot of unconditional love to give so please put in your application to meet me 
Adoption Fee: $500.00
We are a Wisconsin state licensed dog rescue -WI# 402433

***We do not have a central adoption center at this time. All our dogs are in private foster homes within WI. At this time we only place our dogs in areas of WI. The breed of our dogs is our best guess with the help of our veterinarians.
Our Weight Classes are as follows:
0- 25lbs - Small
26- 45lbs - Medium
46-89 - Large
90+ X-large
If you are adopting an adult dog, which we consider 6 months of age or older, your adoption fee includes the following:
Spay/Neuter, Rabies and Distemper shots, dewormed, flea & tick preventative, heartworm tested and microchipped.
If you are adopting a dog younger than 6 months of age, the dog will be up to date on the shots as per the dogs age. The dog will be dewormed, flea/tick preventative and microchipped. We only spay/neuter our dogs by 6 months of age. If you decide to adopt a younger dog than 6 months of age, they will need to be spayed/neutered at one of our preferred clinics. This will be determined by your contract along with the month they should have their surgery. This is included in your adoption fee.
Once you are approved with our rescue, you can meet any one of our dogs within the fosters home. If you are interested in the dog you met, you can take the dog home under our mandatory foster to adopt program. You receive 5 days to see if the dog is the right fit for your home.
If it is, we will conduct the home visit and finalize adoption. If it is not, it is returned to the foster. We are happy to find you another dog that meets your needs in your home.
If a dog is listed as PENDING, a family has met the dog and planning on adopting the dog after the home visit has been conducted. We always suggest sending in an application for a dog because there are times where the dogs are given back to us under the foster to adopt program. There are many reasons dogs are returned but normally it just was not the right fit for all.Please go to WWW.TAILWAGGERS911.COM under HOW TO ADOPT . We have an online application that is very easy to fill out.

animal.description:
PLEASE READ - PLEASE READ - PLEASE READ - PLEASE READ 

Ebe is super cute! BUT please read before applying so you understand that he will need training.

Ebe is a 5 year old that has a long way to go to be the perfect lil' guy that he will definitely be one day. With love, understanding, patience, and mostly time he will be the best dog.  We already love him with all of his naughtiness. He just needs help adjusting to indoor life. He is literally learning every single thing right now.

Ebe still has accidents in the house, but is getting better maybe 60/40 right now. He is not neutered so the first week he was busy marking the place up. 
Belly bands and crating result in some unrelenting howling whining tortured noises and suffering that we are not willing to put him through. Since he was tied outside to a crate maybe it brings up bad memories for him.
Ebe is the sweetest most snuggly lil' guy. He loves to snuggle and cuddle.  He talks and has a lot to say whenever he comes in from outside or when you get home. He is a hilarious dog. 
Ebe does well with other dogs that do not mind his poor manners. Especially with food. Side note, never leave your plate unattended.

He also is learning about toys. He loves toys so much ... he chews a lot. He is still learning that shoes and sofas and cell phone chargers are not for chewing. Miniblinds?! Leave them open so he can see out, or he will fix 'em for ya.

When we first got him he was pretty nippy and growly, so we are not sure about little kids.

He does try to door dash so you have to be alert when opening doors.


Adoption Fee is $350
He is up to date on vaccines and has had a wellness exam, heartworm tested and micro-chipped.

animal.description:
This sweet little velcro leaner is Stella! Isn't she beautiful ?. Stella is a bit timid in the kennel..in a few minutes she will stick to you like glue!! She would love nothing more than to sit with you and watch the world around her. Pretty sure she would love to play too!! We spent almost an hour with her today. She knows how to sit, shake, and is learning "touch" very quickly. She walks amazingly on a leash, super gentle when she takes treats too!! She seems to enjoy "booping" the camera for a selfie Come and meet this sweet little girl !
Volunteer
Kristy and Parker Verant
1/19/21
In summary, she is a scared dog at the shelter. She bit because her dad tried to pull her away from another dog that was attacking Stella. This bite instance is very circumstantial. Anthony and I witnessed no aggression from her today. Special adoption will be to no dog home OR to a home with a dog that compliments Stella with a dog savvy handler.

See below for involved notes about this. 


Stella was taken out of her kennel and walked to a playgroup. She struggled walking from her run to a play group. She pancaked to the floor in fear. She had her tail tucked for awhile in the playgroup. After 70 seconds passed, she made her first social interaction with Anthony and I. She loosened up from there. We took her out for a walk and she did very well. Maintained her sociability etc. Over the course of 30 min, she really blossomed in confidence. To see Stella with Anthony and I go to this link: https://youtu.be/ECvcikiMAMs


Previous owner said their 90 lb female lab jumped Stella when dad came home. Dad got bit while he was trying to free Stella from the hold his other dog had on Stella's back legs. Stella bit him in fear/frenzy. Dogs started to fight because of one of two things 1: resource guarding of the space around dad 2: the arousing situation made the lab snap and Stella. Previous owners state the lab would growl at Stella when Stella was next to her mom. Stella would block the lab from getting on the bed with mom. Lab was already not a fan of Stella. Stella lived well with 2 other male dogs. Stella did well with their grandkids aged 1 thru 4 years old. Stella did well greeting guests in the home.

animal.description:
****Please do not message the rescue asking if this dog is still available; if a dog/puppy is still listed on Petfinder, we are still accepting applications for them. PLEASE READ ENTIRE BIO BEFORE EMAILING****

*Name: Austria

*Age: approximately 3 years old

*Current Weight: 65-70 lbs.

*Adoption fee: $375 (plus $125 spay/neuter deposit, which is refundable when spay/neuter agreement is fulfilled)

*Health: up to date on required vaccines, & microchipped

*Requirements: Another dog in the home, a home with a fully fenced-in yard (physical fences only - no electric fences) due to her skittish nature. 

ABOUT AUSTRIA:
Austria is a very sweet girl who did not have a very good life before she came to SNARR Northeast. She came to us pregnant with a litter of puppies and quickly went into labor soon after arriving in her foster home. She has been an amazing mom to her babies, and now that she has fulfilled her mama duties, she is ready for a forever home of her own! 

Austria is shy when she first meets new people, but she is also very intelligent and once she figures out that you are safe and kind, she will seek out love and affection from you :) She loves to be pet and have her chin scratched, and she will lay down and roll on her back for belly rubs too! Even once she warms up to her people, she is still a bit of a skittish pup. Loud/sudden noises startle her so she should go to a more quiet home without young children. She also does have some separation anxiety and does not do well in a crate. Because of this, we also will require she goes to a home with another friendly, calm dog to keep her company. She has had a troubled past, but we cannot stress enough what a good dog Austria is. She has loved everyone she has met since being in her foster home, and everyone has loved her as well. 

IMPORTANT: This Dog has not yet been altered. For any dog or puppy that is not able to be spayed/neutered prior to adoption, SNARR requires a $125 deposit in addition to your adoption fee, as well as a strictly-enforced signed Spay/Neuter Contract stating you will have this dog altered within 6 months of adoption. The $125 deposit will be returned once the contract has been fulfilled.

 To apply to adopt Austria, fill out an application at www.snarrnortheast.org/applications. 

**Meet and greets will not be scheduled without an approved application.**

-------------------------------------------------------
FAQs -- PLEASE READ ALL BEFORE EMAILING

**Please note that SNARR NE is a volunteer-based organization. While our volunteers will try to respond to you as quickly as possible, it is helpful if you review the following information about our adoption process before emailing:**

- LISTED BREED(S) & AGE: We are taking our best guess on age, breed, and size when fully grown, based on the puppy's/dog's physical appearance and what we might have learned about one or both parents depending on the situation. *NOTE* We rarely know a dog's exact age, nor are we able to tell the true or full breed mix of dogs as our information is limited most of the time. Because we often do not have access to medical records at the time that we are posting dogs to Petfinder, there are sometimes discrepancies between what is posted on Petfinder and what might be listed on a dog's medical records.

- SNARR'S ADOPTION PROCESS: The first step in adopting or meeting a SNARR dog/puppy is to fill out an application at www.snarrnortheast.org/applications. Once we receive your application, one of our adoption application processors will contact you, review our adoption process with you, and answer any additional questions you may have. **We do not go on a first-come-first-serve basis for adoptions, but on best fit for a family and most importantly the puppy or dog.**

- MEETING ADOPTABLE DOGS: Meet and greets will not be scheduled until after your adoption application has been fully processed by one of our adoption processors.

- APPLYING ONLINE: If you fill out an online application, please do so from a computer (not a mobile device), make sure you answer ALL the questions in as much detail as possible, and that you receive a confirmation email. If you do not receive a confirmation email, that means we did NOT receive your application.

- PUPPIES: We do suggest listing a 1st, 2nd and 3rd choice on your application if applying for a puppy with several litter mates.

- ADOPTION FEES:  $495 for puppies / $375 for adults. Adoption Fees for Seniors, Special Needs and Bonded Pairs vary

animal.description:
Titus came to me after his owner, his person that he trusted more than anyone in the world, picked him up and Threw him against a wall breaking his femur!  This sweet boy has been with me ever since.  He had surgery to put a pin in his leg and had to be confined for 8 long weeks.  This poor boy has been thru more than any animal should.  But even after all he has suffered, he is the sweetest, most loving dog you could ever imagine.  
Now Titus is looking for his Real forever home. I am searching for the perfect home for Titus.  I owe him the best life possible.  Titus is not a big boy.  He only weighed 25 lbs on his last checkup and is approximately 18 inches tall from the shoulder.  He is house broken, crate trained, vaccinated and neutered. Titus is approximately 1 ½ years old.  He suffered a terrible injury, but seems unaffected now that he is healed.  No limp, no favoring the leg.  He runs, jumps, wrestles and plays with no issues.  He has no food aggression or resource guarding. However, he is an aggressive chewer with his toys.  He will chew up the toughest toy and has chewed thru a leash or two.  But he doesn’t want to go anywhere, he just wants to play freely.   He is a complete and total lovebug!  He only wants to be where his person is.  He loves to curl up in your lap and cuddle.  Yes, he is small enough to be a lap dog.  Titus also Loves to go for walks and car rides.  
I know the Basenji is a bark less dog, but Titus does bark, probably the Border Collie in him.  Of Course, it is unknown for sure without a dna test, but he has all the wonderful characteristics of a Basenji and is definitely a Border Collie. Titus will be Very responsive to proper training.  He is very smart and an excellent problem solver.  He played with a lot of puzzle toys while healing in confinement.  I had to get him an expert level puzzle and he still mastered it within minutes.  He is friendly and gets along with other dogs very well.  He is ok with cats; he won’t try to kill Anything.  But if they run, the game is on he will definitely chase. But to him its all-in fun.  Titus would make a great agility dog.  He is small, fast and smart.  I would like to see Titus in a family setting, but he would also thrive as a single buddy too as long as he can be by your side.  
I will be taking applications for Titus until the perfect home comes along.  So, if you should apply to adopt him, be prepared for it to be awhile before a decision is made.  All applicants Must provide verifiable vet reference, a video home check and residential stability, meaning no renters.  I know that sounds harsh but too many pets have been rehomed because the owner had to move and “couldn’t take my pet with me”. Titus will Never be discarded or shuffled around again.  Pets are family and should Never be separated from their people because they were not valued as a family member.  
Titus’s perfect home will have a secure yard to play in, Some Fur Siblings, lots of toys to destroy and above all, warmth and security.  His person/family will be warm, friendly, stable and understand that he has been through so much and deserves a happy and loving forever home.   If you are looking for your Forever companion and can provide Titus with these things, please email me and I will send you an application.  It is hard to let him go, he's a special boy.  But it is time for him to find his special someone.  

*The Aurora Dog Pound only adopts out new family members.  Dogs are pack animals and must be included in the home.  This means No pens, No Chains, NO exceptions!

animal.description: Hi! My name is Catalina! I was rescued, while pregnant with my litter of puppies, in Puerto Rico and then brought to the Big Dog Ranch Rescue. I gave birth to 7 puppies here on the ranch. I am a very sweet girl and I love to meet new people. I am an excellent mama to my puppies and I absolutely adore my babies. I play well with other big dogs but appear to have a prey drive and would probably not be happiest in a home with cats. I'd be an excellent pick for a first time adopter and I would be the happiest in a home with a big yard for me to run around and play in. Nothing makes me happier than meeting new people; I love everyone! I would be an excellent dog to bring out and about in public with you because I am so friendly. I am well-trained, even potty-trained, and I love to go on long walks on my leash here at the ranch. My most favorite activity though is going to be snuggling up on the couch next to you!

animal.description: You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Vivian is a wonderful senior dog who had a really rough life before she found her way to rescue. When rescued, she had a single puppy and not producing milk; she was severely underweight; she was heartworm positive, and she had horrible ear infections. She is gaining weight, but very slowly. She survived years of neglect but she truly loves people. She has limited hearing and because she was starved in the past, she is very protective of her food or treats from other animals. Vivian has been fostering at a doggy daycare. She does good with other dogs as long as there is no food/treats involved. We are not sure if she would be possessive over toys as she doesn't have much interest in them other than to have a stuffy in her bed with her. We believe she would do best with children 7 or older who are respectful of dogs. She would thrive in a home where she could be the center of someone's hearts and live the rest of her life with all the love she has missed in the past.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.
Hi, I'm Meeko! I'm a Siberian Husky/German Shepherd mix with an estimated DOB of 10-8-2016. I am a tall and long boy weighing about 70lbs. I am a very good, sweet boy. I love attention and getting pets. If you stop, I'll be really cute and paw at you to remind you that I still want all of the pets. I LOVE playing fetch with balls, squeaky toys, or really anything you will throw. I am excellent at dropping it and will even go find the ball when I accidentally lose it! If it were up to me, I would fetch all day. Being outside is my favorite. Even though I'm from Arkansas, I LOVE the snow! I also love going for walks, even though I zig-zag and pull a lot. I will pull and whine when I see other dogs or people because I love them!

At night I sleep in the kennel, but the kennel is not my favorite. My foster parents are trying to kennel train me, otherwise I would totally sleep in their bed at night! I don't like being alone, so I whine when I'm in my kennel. I'll need my furever home to continue helping me with learning that my kennel is good! That means no shared walls for me. I go for walks with my foster dog brother Bruno, and we love it. My foster parents say I need slow intros to dogs, because I get too excited and don't take cues when other dogs are not wanting to play. For this reason, I am not a dog park dog and would do great as an only dog so I can get all of the attention. I am NOT good with cats as I have a high prey drive. I would do best without small animals because of my prey drive. I have a lot of energy, so I would love a fenced in yard to run around and play fetch. My foster parents have a 5ft. fence, but I have never tried to jump it or escape. If you're looking for a big, sweet boy and adventure or exercise buddy, please apply so we can meet and I can go to my furever home!

Interested in adopting this lovable animal? Please go to our website www.wagsmn.org and fill out an Adoption Application. Once the application is processed, a Wags representative will contact you, answer any questions you may have, and set up a time/location for a meet and greet! A home visit is required prior to adoption.

Thank you for choosing to adopt!

Breed and temperament determination: Wags & Whiskers Animal Rescue attempts to determine breed and temperament using a combination of looks, information provided to us at intake, and our experience with the animal while in our Rescue. We do not guarantee this determination.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Cooper came to the shelter as an owner surrender. His person could not have a dog like him where she lives. She was informed of this after having Cooper for over a year. Cooper is a short and squishy pit bull type guy. He is stocky and compact. Cooper has a delightful and happy personality and is always ready for action and fun. He has been neutered and chipped but we will get him vet checked before adoption. His fee is $125.

Cooper is looking for either an adult only home or one with kids over 10. He does need a little basic obedience training but is pretty in tune to his person and is eager to please. Cooper does need to be the only dog in the home. We're erring on the side of caution regarding cats.

NOTE: We are closed to the public but are doing adoptions via private appointment once an application has been submitted and approved. Applications can be submitted right at our website, mchs.rescuegroups.org.

We are located at 101 22nd St. SE in Austin, right next to the airport. It's exit 180B off of I-90, right off of 218 South.

We do require that potential adopters be at least 21 years old and that any resident dogs be up to date on vaccinations, heartworm testing/preventative, and spayed or neutered.

animal.description:
Meet Hope! 

Hello, my name is Hope. I'm 13 years old and 35 pounds. You might notice by my pictures that I'm blind, so that means my other senses are heightened. I will be depending on your voice quite a bit in the first few days that im with you. I will follow it to learn my surroundings, and once I know them I do quite well getting around on my own. I will also depend on your voice to let me know how to feel until I get used to noises. If I hear something unfamiliar, I might bark, so your calm, reassuring voice will help me to know everything is okay. I get along with dogs who are my size or larger, but the smaller ones, well, I happen to think they are toys. This also means I might not get along with cats since they are smaller than me, although I've not been around any in my foster home. I prefer to eat by myself since I can't tell if someone will try to steal my food, and I really like my food. I don't have any kids in my foster home either, but I bet older kids who are calm and quiet would be okay for me to live with. I'm a really good girl about going potty outside, and I even know how to use a doggy door if you have one! I'm a pretty laid back lady and will be more than happy to snuggle up on my blanket next to you for a movie night. You watch, I'll listen. If you'd rather read a book, I'm happy to take a nap next to you. I sure 'hope' my new family finds me soon so we can start our forevers together! 

Albert's Dog Lounge is a transporting dog rescue, meaning that we rescue many of our dogs from high kill shelters in areas of dog overpopulation. We are a specialty rescue focusing primarily on senior and special needs dogs.  The vast majority of our dogs come from the Houston, TX area where we have an entire team of volunteers, coordinators, and fosters. We do also work with local shelters, rescues, and owners.  If you apply for a dog that is currently in our local Houston program, we will work to get your dog transported to WI as quickly as possible. We ask that you have patience during this time of uncertainty and unprecedented dog adoptions nationwide. 

Learn more about Albert's Dog Lounge, our mission, and adoption policies by visiting Albertsdoglounge.org. 

Our process includes an approved application, reference checks, a homevisit, and then a meet and greet with the dog. Adoption fee is $275.

Begin your application process by copying this link into your web browser: https://www.albertsdoglounge.org/apply

WI Dept. Of Agriculture License Number: 474085-DS

animal.description:
Storm ACCT-A-81617

Bio: Storm enjoys hiking and running (even though she likes to stop for sniffs) she does well in car rides and is always excited to go on adventures. She gets excited (sometimes reactive) and pulls towards other dogs and cats on walks so might be best as an only pet. She is also jumpy with people and still working on her manners so potentially needs a home without small children.

She is house broken and sleeps in her crate. 

We will work with trainers on anxiety and mouthiness so hopefully those behaviors will resolve soon! 

Intake Type: Stray
Sex: Female
Altered: Yes
Age: 3Y

Medical Observation: (12/27) Normal, eyes red

Behavior Observation:
(12/28) Per Lifesaving -- Kennel Presentation - Nervous. Difficult to remove from kennel. Fearful and avoids leash. Would approach kennel door to sniff treats and my hand, but would not take treats and dodged leash. After many attempts she came to the kennel door for some ham and I was able to leash her. Walking through the kennels she is fearful and zigzags a bit. On return, she entered the kennel easily and let me remove the leash.
Leash Skills - Pulls Minimally On Leash.
Handleability - Loose/Allows all handling. Initially after removing her from the kennel Storm was nervous and tense with ears back and tail tucked. We placed her in the foster office and after she sniffed the perimeter of the room she relaxed and had her ears perked and tail wagging, and would approach us to solicit attention, get pets and give kisses. Allows pets all over.
Tag - No interest. Toys - No interest. Evaluated Gold - just needs high value treats to encourage her to exit kennel.
(12/27) Per Vet Staff -- Fearful; QAR
(12/27) Per Finder -- calm and loving with people but aggressive with dogs (nipped at another dog), does not like other dogs, good on leash - does not pull.

This animal is currently available from foster care through ACCT Philly's Adoptions Programs. This animal is not onsite. If the foster has not listed a personal email, contact foster@acctphilly.org to be put in touch with the foster. 

We encourage you to visit our shelter during our adoption hours to view our complete selection of available animals. In preparation for your visit, please make sure to visit http://www.acctphilly.org/adopt/ to review our adoption requirements, hours of operation, upcoming events, and more! 

Is this your missing pet? If you believe so, please make sure to follow the instructions listed at http://www.acctphilly.org/lostpet/ so that we can make sure that you are reunited as soon as possible!

animal.description:
This is Belle. She is a very sweet girl who has lots of energy as a nine month old puppy would.  She and my golden play and wrestle out in the back yard.  He is 13 so he gets worn out much faster than she does.  He lets her know when he has had enough.  She also gets along with my 9 year old 9 lb little terrier mix  as well.    

 
She loves her toys.  Anything with stuffing though will be dead in about 5 seconds but toys with no stuffing have worked much better.  She loves to chase a ball. We have glow in the dark ones for nighttime.   She also loves her flat duck that looks like a frisbee.  A good “kong” with the stuffings she loves and it keeps her busy in the crate.  Just the regular kong is about the right level for her.  Also a wobbler she likes too.  Very entertaining for her mind.    She doesn’t mind sharing toys with my boys (dogs) but things that are much smellier like a bully stick or knuckle bone, not as well, but I have to separate my boys (dogs) when we get the good stuff out.    For a nine month old puppy she really has been so good.  Only two things have really been chewed on and no accidents in the house at all. 

She is crate trained.  She is so so smart.  She can sit, shake (very close almost working on it still) , lay down, go get on her bed when asked.  I think with additional training she could do anything.   She walks pretty good on a leash.  We use a harness and with just a little practice and a warmer day I know without a doubt she would improve immediately. 

She has not been scared of thunder or storms, but loud noises sometimes scare her.   She will improve over time once she is with her forever family.  She also loves looking out my front glass door and watching the world go by.  If she sees people and or dog or cat she will speak about it and let you know but nothing to crazy. 

She can jump right high so a 6 ft privacy fence would be best for her.

She would love to be snuggled on the couch and in bed with you so she feels really safe and close to you.  She does become very interested in the TV as you can see in a few of the pics and also the fish tank. 

“Belle”  has LOTS OF LOVE  to give to a family.    She would do well with a family that is active and will take her walking and play with her. 

Please let us know if you are interested in her.  Would love to talk to you more about her.  Look soon for more updates. 

After reading this pet's info, if you are still interested in adopting, please fill out the online adoption application found at www.realgooddogrescue.com 

The ideal home for this Real Good Dog will have a secure fenced yard.  A solid history of excellent vet care for current or previous pets is required.  Preference will be given to applicants who have specific breed experience.  

Please visit www.realgooddogrescue.com to submit an electronic application if you are interested in adopting this or any other Real Good Dog.

Meet Alpine!  This adorable guy was pulled from the euthanasia list the day before he was going to be put to sleep.  We can't believe someone didn't go to the pound to reclaim him!  He's so incredibly sweet and a great size at right around 50 pounds.  

Alpine seems to like other dogs just fine.  He is good on a leash and would love to be your next partner for adventure!  Alpine isn't currently living in a foster home, so we are unsure of his level of housetraining.  

Alpine is very outgoing and just a sweetie!  He certainly deserves a home, and soon!


Alpine's adoption fee is $450 which includes his neuter, current vaccinations, negative heartworm test, registered microchip, and transport costs.

He is available through Paw Pals of Hale Center in Hale Center, TX through Project Freedom Ride. He would be transported on one of the PFR transports (next transport is Mar 4) to either Seattle, WA, Mt Vernon, WA, or Portland, OR. animal.description:
LOOKING FOR A BEST FRIEND:  3 years old / 40 lbs.

Hi, my name is Prancer!  I came to Mostly Mutts from animal control and they could tell I had puppies in the past, but I’ve now been spayed – putting my puppy raising days behind me.  Now, I am ready to become a loved family member. I’m currently in the prison foster/training program offsite and learning so much! 

• OTHER DOGS/CATS/KIDS:  Let’s meet. I came in with another dog and I play well with two of the other Mutts in the prison program, but I can play vocally at times which not all dogs like.  I also met a couple of dogs in my short break foster home and – while we played well together outside, I tried to dominate them when we were inside. If you have a dog let’s meet to make sure we can be friends. / Cats unknown / I’ve met some kids while at Mostly Mutts (age 10+), so children around that age or older may be nice in my new home and – of course, let’s meet!  I was not fond of kids riding bikes in the parking lot near me, just so you are aware of that.

• PERSONALITY/ENERGY LEVEL:  I am a very sweet, energetic, and playful young girl with lots of love to offer my new family.  I have a fun, friendly and confident demeanor, which is sure to make for some great memories in my new home. I am also very social and am happiest when spending time with my people and being very active with them. I’m curious and interested in everything! / My energy level is 7-9, so I am looking for a family that wants to include their dog in on all the fun and exercise with them.

• SKILLS/CRATE/POTTY: As a student in the Mostly Mutts University training program, I’ve proven to be smart and very trainable, and I’ve quickly learned the following commands: ‘sit’, ‘down’, ‘stay’, ‘come’, ‘drop it’, and ‘leave it’ as well as proper door etiquette and accepting friendly stranger without jumping. I bet you can teach me even more – including polishing my leash skills, as I tend to jump, pull, and lunge at cars while on my leash right now, so please keep a good hold / I don’t love the crate, but I don’t make a fuss once I am in it.  I’d just rather be with you / My potty manners have been good on the prison program schedule.

• LIKES/DISLIKES:  I love to play - especially with my people. I can become mouthy during playtime due to my enthusiasm, but I’m working on this with my trainer. I also love treats so my continued training should be lots of fun.  In the short break foster home I visited, I really loved running around in the fenced back yard while they looked on and spent time with me outside / Sudden noises startle me and – aside from the issue with some other dogs and bike riders mentioned above, I can’t think of any other dislikes right now, though I am sure I would not be happy if I did not get the love, exercise, training and attention on which I thrive!     

• MEDICAL:   I'm current on vaccinations, micro-chipped and spayed.

I am looking for an active family to have lots of adventures with and who will love me furever!  My adoption fee is $299.00, and I’m located in Kennesaw, Ga.

animal.description:
Zoey is an Am Staff/German Shepherd mix. She’s 2 years old and weighs 55 lbs. 

Zoey was an owner surrender to Pasco County Animal Services and we took her in because she was terrified, thin and missing hair due to fleas. Sudden movements, raised voices, loud noises all seemed to frighten her. While in our home for the past 5 weeks she’s made an amazing improvement, she is no longer fearful. We have shown her love and understanding during her transition. She knows she’s safe with us. She has steadily gained weight and all her hair has grown in. She’s gorgeous. 

We are looking for an adopter who will show her the same love and understanding that we have. They will need to go slow and have patience. She is a bit fearful of men. 
Once Zoey is comfortable she’s a total love bug and big lap dog. 

An active family would suit her best. She would make an excellent partner to jog, bike or hike with. She really enjoys the outdoors. 

Requirements for adopting Zoey:
- Must have at least 1 other playful dog; she’s great with both large and small dogs
- No cats
- Kids 10+ (she will not hurt a small child, she is afraid of them. Visiting small children are ok)
- A fenced yard is preferred. 
-Must work from home, be retired or work only part time; Zoey does not like to be alone. 

She is spayed, microchipped and current on vaccinations. 

*Potential adopters must live no further than an hour of Wesley Chapel*

*We accept email inquiries only*

animal.description:
No seriously, adopt the smartest, most agile, and faithful malinois. Working dog experience is a must in order to be considered for this guy. He will require daily exercise and mental stimulation or he will find himself in the dog house (don't worry taster we don't judge). Taster has come along way since he came to us as a true "maligator", with no off switch. Taster will require an experienced home that sets boundaries . Even though taster is in a foster home with young children, we recommend older kids as he may knock over the younger ones and when excited sometimes gets a little mouthy (not in a mean way but playful and has been working really hard on not doing so since we took him in). He does well with dogs of all sizes(his foster home has dogs ranging from one pound up to fifty pounds) but may be too much for smaller dogs as he loves to play and doesn't realize his size. He does well with horses and doesn't bother with them as long as his person is with him. His foster has crate trained him and he does amazing, doesn't have any accidents and no jail breaks. He has slept out of the crate and done well too. He's working on and doing well on a leash. He's learned sit, drop it, lay down, and roll over. He's currently working on the stay command and his recall is perfect. Taster loves the water and you will often find him in the smallest of puddles if he can find them. He's a faithful dog who loves his people and he's attached himself to the nine year old little girl in his foster home and is her constant shadow. He's picked up on new tricks within minutes of learning them. Hes ben introduce to some agility and would excel in it. He's a special dog that will continue to do and be amazing in the right home. If taster joins your family, you'll see just what a special gift you've received with him.

Our dog adoption fees range from $150-$240 depending on the dog's age, and our cat fees range from $45-120. They are all spayed/neutered, microchipped with lifetime registration, and have received age appropriate vaccines. If you would like to meet one of our pets, please do the online application at
https://www.petstablished.com/adoption_form/12113/generic
You only need to do it once for our organization, regardless of how many of our dogs you are interested in.

animal.description: This unbelievably adorable face belongs to Rollo. Impounded at the shelter, Rollo got wind of our organization and used his one allotted call to ask if we'd come down and spring him. One look at his mug shot and we were there in a heartbeat; already in love with that face. On the ride over, he let us know that he has some physical ailments: cataracts (causing some sight impairment), some hearing impairment and a heart murmur. We didn't care. As far as we're concerned, he's perfect! Although shy when he first arrived, it didn't take him long to come out of his shell; or map out his new digs. He even met a couple of ladies who he's become quite fond of; oftentimes sharing the comfiest bed in the suite for an afternoon snuggle. And it's not just his canine pals he likes socializing with; he's beginning to really enjoy being around humans, too. Still not 100% sure of how to courageously ask for affection, he's getting there. We don't think he'd be one for long, romantic walks on the beach, but he does appreciate time outdoors for a breath of fresh air. Despite being in his golden years, Rollo still has plenty of life and love to give. We hope you'll consider our beloved friend as your next forever companion.

animal.description: Poor Moira has been through quite a lot. Adopted by her family with her best friend (who was quickly returned to the shelter), she was given up by her family because they couldn't care for her any longer. A sad situation, but we consider ourselves pretty lucky to have her in our lives. She's about as perfect as can be. Although she doesn't change her wigs and apparel as often as her namesake from ""Schitt's Creek"", she definitely shares the spunk and personality! Every time you look at that adorable face, there's a smile hanging around it. She is always happy to see you; waddling her way into your space with an ever-present, happy tail. She can be apprehensive of being picked up at times, but will never turn down the opportunity to receive your swoons, coos and affection. Moira is kind to her canine friends, but really cares more about the humans. She will do just about anything to be the center of your attention. Lovingly referred to as the ""baby hamster"" by staff, this beautiful senior still has lots of life and love to give. She'd be the most loyal companion you could ever ask for. Won't you please consider Moira for your next forever friend?

animal.description:
Leyton is currently enjoying the life of a foster dog, and according to her foster parents, Leyton might just be the world's sweetest pittie! She is a total snuggle bug with a very gentle and even-keeled temperament. Like the classic Staffy, Leyton is extremely obedient, loyal, and eager to please. She loves to cuddle up on the couch and give you sweet kisses. She is content to nap quietly all day while her foster mom works in another part of the house. Leyton loves going on walks and weekend hikes too. Since she just came from a home, she is 100% housebroken, crate trained, and knows her basic commands like sit, shake, and stay. We originally pulled her from a shelter in Riverside County in late December 2016. She was adopted a little over a week later, but recently returned to us December 2020, nearly 4 years later. Her previous home consisted of another dog, a cat, and 5 children. Leyton grew protective of her family and domain, so when the kids would leave the doors and gates open, she would get out and go after neighborhood dogs. Leyton can and has been good with other dogs when properly introduced inside her home. She is not suitable for off-leash environments like the dog park or dog beach. She is great with cats, kids, and adults alike. She can be a little timid upon first meeting new people, but she warms up quickly. She is looking for a secure home with tall fences and old enough humans who can follow instructions on how to keep doors closed at all times. Leyton is 5 years old and weighs 53 pounds. If you think you might be the right home for Leyton, please apply!

In the meantime, you can learn more about Leyton and follow her daily foster adventures on Instagram at @theserialfoster!To initiate the adoption process for this dog, please complete our online application by clicking below. Your adoption coordinator will respod to you via email once they receive your application: www.thebarkinglot.net/adopt

animal.description:
Available Wednesday, January 20th at 7pm on our Adoptions Uncrated website. 
https://www.followyourheartanimalrescue.org/shop
Dezi is a sweet and energetic girl. She gets pretty excited so would be better in a home with older children that she isn't going to knock over. She needs a home without livestock (chickens, pigs, etc) or cats as they are too much fun to chase.

Dezi and her pups joined the rescue when her pups were about 5 weeks old. Little is known about her prior life as it was very late on a Sunday evening when she was dropped off with her pups. 
She is a large girl, possibly lab/shepherd blend and her ideal weight is somewhere between 60-65lbs when filled out. 

During her time with the rescue we learned that she is quite the puppy herself in age and manners. Dezi does want to please but can be impulsive.....such as in attempting to swipe a snack right out of your hand, jumping up to give a face to face kiss etc. she is very friendly and loves all humans but might be knock over small children. Dezi has a pretty high prey drive and thinks livestock would be better snacks than roommates. Dezi does good with cats but due to her drive would say constant supervision would be necessary. Dezi can be quite rough during play and while she gets along with other dogs her exuberance for life could be very annoying to the wrong dog so if considering adopting as companion to another dog intros would be necessary.

animal.description:
Also in need of a Foster home ~
NMDOG CAPTAIN KANGAROO is available for adoption! Please send an inquiry via this Petfinder link Or...to learn more about the NMDOG Adoption Program, please visit this link on our website - www.nmdog.org/adopt 

ROO is 5 yrs old & he is a verrry good boy! He is wiggly, he is squiggly, he is goofy & fun!! But that comes after he warms up to you a little bit, not right at first. Placement with a female dog would be considered based on human experience & resident dog temperament. Ideally....we are seeking a home for CAPTAIN KANGAROO where he can be the only Doggie kid, continue confidence boosting & enrichment activities...as he explores his brand new world ? We expect ROO & his peeps to be awesome & responsible Breed Ambassadors. Cats are unknown & we ask that children be 10+! 
____________________________________________

As an all volunteer, foster based, 501(c)3 non profit rescue, NMDOG is always in need of new, approved foster & adoptive homes in order to continue our Mission: to serve & protect New Mexico's Forgotten Dogs!! #UNchained

If you see a dog you are interested in that says "in need of a foster home", we are currently seeking a temporary foster home for that dog in order to provide them with the cozy & loving experience of a home environment while we work hard to find their forever family. This also frees up space & funds, which enables us to save another life. There is never a cost to foster for NMDOG & you will have the dedicated support of the NMDOG TEAM every step of the way. We take the time to really get to know the needs & personalities of our kids & we go the extra mile to ensure we make the best possible match...setting our dogs & their humans up for success! To learn more about the NMDOG Foster Program, please visit this link on our website - www.nmdog.org/foster

Our adoption fee is $250 which includes; a 7 week NMDOG obedience/bonding class with your new Dog (classes are located in Abq & are also offered to our Foster Guardians at no charge), a complimentary vet wellness check & our dogs come with all of the supplies they need to get started on a trial adoption in their new home. All adopted dogs also receive free or discounted goodies & services from many of our awesome community partners!! Grooming, food, training, boarding, pet sitting & more.

NMDOG doesn't cut any corners when it comes to the care & placement of our dogs. When a dog enters the NMDOG program, they are guaranteed to receive the very best of care. All of our available dogs have received a full medical & behavioral clearance prior to placement. They are (at the very minimum) spayed or neutered, UTD on age appropriate vaccinations, microchipped, dewormed, Heartworm tested & currently on HW/flea & tick preventative. Due to the nature of our work, many of the dogs we rescue need much more extensive care before they are cleared for adoption. At NMDOG, we stand by our dogs for life & we make a promise to always be there for them (& their people) should they ever need us. .

Please contact us with your interest in becoming a treasured NMDOG Foster Guardian or FoReVeR Guardian Angel to one of our amazing dogs in need! Direct email contact for applications ~ TiffanyN@nmdog.org
We look forward to hearing from you & answering any questions you may have. WooF!!
