GoGo is a very sweet girl...but due to her history of life on a chain in isolation, unlike most Huskies.....GoGo prefers to be the only dog in the home & no dog parks.. Cats are unknown. GoGo is appx 4 years old & shes petite at 45#. She is snuggly, loves to have her belly rubbed & she loves to play "toss" with her squeaky hedgehog! GoGo will need a 6ft fence to keep her safe & an active family to keep her happy! Shes ready to start a new life of adventure with a human family that can keep up! 
____________________________________________

As an all volunteer, foster based, 501(c)3 non profit rescue, NMDOG is always in need of new, approved foster & adoptive homes in order to continue our Mission: to serve & protect New Mexico's Forgotten Dogs!! #UNchained

If you see a dog you are interested in that says "in need of a foster home", we are currently seeking a temporary foster home for that dog in order to provide them with the cozy & loving experience of a home environment while we work hard to find their forever family. This also frees up space & funds, which enables us to save another life. There is never a cost to foster for NMDOG & you will have the dedicated support of the NMDOG TEAM every step of the way. We take the time to really get to know the needs & personalities of our kids & we go the extra mile to ensure we make the best possible match...setting our dogs & their humans up for success! To learn more about the NMDOG Foster Program, please visit this link on our website - www.nmdog.org/foster

Our adoption fee is $250 which includes; a 7 week NMDOG obedience/bonding class with your new Dog (classes are located in Abq & are also offered to our Foster Guardians at no charge), a complimentary vet wellness check & our dogs come with all of the supplies they need to get started on a trial adoption in their new home. All adopted dogs also receive free or discounted goodies & services from many of our awesome community partners!! Grooming, food, training, boarding, pet sitting & more.

NMDOG doesn't cut any corners when it comes to the care & placement of our dogs. When a dog enters the NMDOG program, they are guaranteed to receive the very best of care. All of our available dogs have received a full medical & behavioral clearance prior to placement. They are (at the very minimum) spayed or neutered, UTD on age appropriate vaccinations, microchipped, dewormed, Heartworm tested & currently on HW/flea & tick preventative. Due to the nature of our work, many of the dogs we rescue need much more extensive care before they are cleared for adoption. At NMDOG, we stand by our dogs for life & we make a promise to always be there for them (& their people) should they ever need us. .

Please contact us with your interest in becoming a treasured NMDOG Foster Guardian or FoReVeR Guardian Angel to one of our amazing dogs in need! Direct email contact for applications ~ TiffanyN@nmdog.org
We look forward to hearing from you & answering any questions you may have. WooF!!

ROADIE is an incredible spirit looking for his special SoulHuman to adventure through life with. He is a TriPawd Wooly Husky with considerations in place for the best interest of the health & longevity of his 3 remaining legs...as well as his "King of the World" bigger than life, adorable, FloofFace personality. 

- ROADIE will need a home with a majority of carpet in the house & grass in the yard. He has no problem with stairs as with a secure/carpeted place to "land". 
- ROADIE will do best as the only dog in the home. No cats, pocket pets or birds & we ask that any children be 10+. 
- ROADIE needs a 5ft min fence or wall to keep him safe. 
- No dog parks for ROADIE. 

None of these considerations will keep ROADIE from finding a home....they will ensure that ROADIE finds the right home :) Being a Tripawd doesnt keep ROADIE from going on hikes, doing zoomies in the yard or playing on his long line with at the (dog friendly, human) parks. ROADIE is ready to find his special FoReVeR Family!! 

He is super duper snuggly, soft & he sings the beautiful songs of his people....WooWoo ArhooRooooo WooWooWoo!! ROADIE rides great in the car & he LoooVes going on daytrips, weekendenders & overnights, or long road trip adventures. He is housetrained, cratetrained & walks well on his leash + harness (except when he sees a chipmunk, a roadrunner or a bunny rabbit - then all you can do is hold on & you have to!) Sometimes ROADIE likes to play chase, ruffhouse, use his best friend as a chew toy & wrestle "Rawr Rawr Rawr"! But if you're a Husky person, you get this & no explanation is needed :)

animal.description: Sweet Twilight is searching for couch hangouts and playful romps in the yard or the park! She can be both chill and playful - she's happy to tailor herself to your house. She likes walks and knows how to run on a leash properly! She will match your energy, and when she wants to go out, but you haven't noticed, you'll be wooed outside with Chewbacca noises. She has weaned her puppies and is ready to move on with her life! We are not sure how she'll get along with other dogs. She can be rambunctious when playing, so a large dog playmate would be more her style. She's not a fan of those felines, but she is learning 'leave it' when the neighbor's outdoor kitties wander by to tease her. She jumps up to greet her humans, so kids older than 5 or 6 would be ideal. She is house-trained, and doing well on her crate-training. Her best life would be an active home, and a couch to veg out on. If you are looking for a really chill pup with a lot of snuggles to give, who is great on leash for jogs, come meet Twilight. She's ready for some love after being a wonderful patient mama to nine puppies!

animal.description: Viper has proven to be a wonderful animal companion, and has come a long way. He has learned to walk well on leash, he knows all of his basic commands, he will wait until instructed to eat, and will stay seated before leaving for his walks. He prefers to stay away from other pups on his leash walks. He is also a very quiet pup and will only bark when he's having a silly dream! This sweet, affectionate, and loving guy wants to be with his person more than anything else. He prefers to sleep most of the day, doesn't like toys or games, mostly he just wants to chill and live the good life of retirement. Viper would do well in a home where he is the only pup as he really only likes to socialize with other dogs for a few minutes. He would also thrive in a home that can provide him lots of love and attention. Viper will take time to warm up in a new home, and would love a patient human who is experienced at working with anxious pups and larger breeds. He would ideally love a home with a yard where he can stretch his legs and get his exercise running around in the yard. Come meet this sweet boy, he's waiting for his loving furever home!

Bear
Male
Shepard Mix
65-70#

Bear is a great boy who is eager to please. He is getting along with 3 other dogs in the home. Bear does need to gain a little more weight, but otherwise he is doing very well.
Dog Friendly: Yes, is very playful with others
Cat friendly: Unknown
Kid friendly: Yes, he might knock over smaller children with his rambunctiousness.

Potty trained: Yes, he does have access to a doggy door.
Leash trained: Needs work on walking on a leash, he pulls. A martingale collar would work well for Bear.
Kennel trained: Bear has not messed in his kennel even once. We had an unexpected long period of time away and he still held it.

BIOGRAPHY: Bear was a stray in Oklahoma and had been in a shelter there for several months with no interest from anyone. He was put on the euthanasia list and that is when we brought him into our rescue to save his life.

Behavioral Issues: Bear barks some when he gets excited. He will also jump up on you.

Medical Issues: None Known.

Adoption Fee: $200
Location: Pratt, KS

animal.description:
Shay and her brother Cherokee were left behind when a tenant vacated a rental property and left them behind. Shay has a friendly personality and is very energetic. She LOVES people and gets very excited when meeting new friends. She is working on leash training and can walk well when she is calm. She loves to run and is bouncy and playful but she has also been the perfect work from home companion who is content just snuggling up next to you.

Shay may get along with other dogs, having lived with one, but introductions should be made slowly. Shay is a firm NO for cats and has never lived with kids, but after a short stay in a home with a toddler, we know that Shay gets nervous around young kids. She will need to be in a home with maybe teen-aged children or adults only. Shay would do best in a home with a yard & plenty of room for her to play. A fence would be required because she will not know to return when called right away. Shay will need a patient family that understands she will need time to adjust to house manners, but he is super intelligent and a quick learner!

Apply to adopt SHAY LONESTAR at www.EHRDOGS.org!

animal.description:
Animal Profile: Zeke is a gorgeous sable German Shepherd that is looking for a home that has experience with Shepherds. He was purchased from a breeder at 6 weeks old, and was mostly an outdoor dog that didn't get much in the way of obedience training. He knows basic commands like 'sit' and 'down', and is house and crate trained. Zeke is playful and affectionate and wants to be with his people. He loves carrying around toys in the house, and will even carry them on his walk. His leash manners are a work in progress, and he will need a confident handler to continue his training as he is strong and motivated. Zeke can be leash reactive and dog selective. He has lived with other dogs in the past but his ideal home would have no other pets. Due to his size, strength, and tendency to jump and mouth when he is playing, we will not be considering homes with young children. Zeke loves to play fetch and tug, is crate trained, house trained and has good manners inside. Zeke would excel in a home that was interested in dog sports like rally, nosework, barnhunt or agility. Zeke is up for any adventure but also had an off switch and can hang out at home. He requires a securely fenced yard. We will not be considering first time dog owners for Zeke.

Seattle Foster Update: Coming Soon!

Adoption Info:
Adoption fee is $400 which includes spay/neuter, all core vaccinations, microchip, heartworm test and health certificate. Your adoption fee may be tax deductible as Dog Gone Seattle is a federal 501c3 organization.

Apply online:
www.doggoneseattle.org/adoption-application

animal.description:
Kylo was originally rescued from a crowded Texas shelter with a broken jaw that he'd received from blunt force trauma and a skin condition that left him looking pitiful. Life became infinitely better for Kylo when he was rescued came to New Jersey, where he was adopted a short time later, but sadly had to be returned to because the family found that they just could not give him the time, training, and attention he required. When alone, he developed some destructive behaviors that we are working on correcting. He is a chewer--he needs lots of chew toys to keep him on the right track. He also needs a confident handler, an owner with experience in dog ownership and training. Because of his rough start, Kylo gets nervous very easily in social situations and that can display itself in more aggressive ways. Having an established, confident adult dog in the house will help with this, but that dog would also have to be okay with Kylo's sometimes rough play.

Kylo is a very energetic pup, who plays hard and loves harder! Even though he has actually become fairly large at almost 50lbs, he still thinks he's a lap puppy and will spend all day in your lap if you let him. Because of his nervousness, combined with his energy, size, and strength, Kylo needs to be in a home without children, where there will be very low traffic levels from visitors. Kylo needs an adopter that is very active but also around for him - he does have some nervousness when left alone, and can get into mischief if not monitored. He would do best with owners who work from home and can take breaks to exercise him. He knows to go to the door when he needs to go potty, but he still has occasional accidents and needs to be walked regularly. He also needs an outlet for all of his energy and excitement, so a fenced yard would be preferred.

Kylo is very food motivated and will do pretty much anything you ask of him if a treat is involved. He also loves to ride in the car.

Apply to adopt KYLO LONESTAR at www.EHRDOGS.org!

animal.description:
Dakota is a 1.5 year old Australian Shepherd/Foxhound mix (DNA test) although we know he doesn't look it! He is also mixed with several other breeds. He was adopted as a puppy but recently had to come back to Eleventh Hour to find his new forever home.

Dakota is a very smart boy who learns easily. He knows lots of commands: Sit, stay, paw, lay down, roll over, drop it, leave it (if fixated on something while on a walk). When being fed his meals if you tell him "Sit/Stay", then put his food bowl on ground, he will wait until you tell him "go ahead or OK" then will eat his food. He can be a very good boy.

Dakota was very under socialized as a pup so he is afraid of new people. He definitely prefers women over men, but he can warm up to men fairly quickly as well, and he cannot be in a home with children. Dakota needs a slow introduction to new people as he is very scared. He is the SWEETEST boy ever once he is comfortable with you - kisses, hugs, everything. Dakota is dog friendly and would actually benefit from having another dog in the home with him, but it must be a very confident dog.

If you think you could provide Dakota with the loving home he deserves, please fill out an application at www.ehrdogs.org & be sure to mention his name!

Thor is a smart boy that already knows some commands, including "sit," "down," and "shake" along with the command of "stay...no way!" He is adaptable and a big, strong malamute that would love to be part of a pack of his very own. He is friendly to people, curious, and already knows the command of "sit." He does really well in cars, taking the opportunity to chill and even nap. He will need some help with his leash training, which is not surprising based on his history as he has likely not had a lot of experience. He enjoys attention and being pet and we are confident he will really enjoy learning about the finer things in life - like indoor snuggles and lots of adventures! Interested in sponsoring? animal.description:
Sweet Momma Goldie has settled into her new foster. She is loving being an inside dog and loving her new soft bed even more. She’ll climb on it and sleep for hours. Goldie is the momma that was attacked by another dog in Washington county along with her puppies. She had a terrible infection in her front leg that was so severe she couldn’t even use it. After a week on strong antibiotics her leg healed good and she’s feeling great. She’s a sweet sweet girl. She’s shy at first but quickly warms up. She hasn’t shown any aggression to people just a little standoffish until she realizes you are ok. She does well with other dogs but can be a little intimidated at first so she needs slow intros. Once she’s use to everyone she loves to play. She’s not fond with cats. She did well with a 3 year old. She is she is house and crate trained. Doesn’t seem to be a chewer. She is pretty mellow but will play. We were told she is a purebred black mouth cur . around 2 years old. She is utd, hw negative (tested below detectable levels) and spayed. 

All dogs have a $175 adoption fee which includes vet check, age appropriate shots (atleast 2 sets for puppies), dewormer, heartworm test (if over 6 months), rabies (if atleast 16 weeks) and spay/neuter!

Puppies/Dogs that are not available for adoption due to vetting not being complete can be reserved with an approved application and a non refundable $50 deposit. This deposit is applied to your adoption fee and the remaining $125 is due at pick up.

Wags and Whiskers is an all-volunteer rescue. We also have full-time jobs and Families. We will try to answer all questions and applications in a timely manner. Please be patient and bear with us . Do not contact Parkway Animal Hospital as they are a vet clinic and can not answer questions on behalf of Wags and Whiskers. All questions and comments must go directly through the rescue. Thank you for your understanding.

animal.description: 6 year old Marilyn ended up at animal control when her owner lost his home. She is a friendly, sweet girl that loves kids. Marilyn loves her toys and human attention, but doesn’t necessarily want to share with another dog. She would love to be an only dog in her forever home where she can be the sole focus. Marilyn does well in a crate and will put herself in there even when the door is open. She enjoys running with her ball and will require a fenced yard. This princess deserves a family to call her own! If interested in adopting Marilyn, apply at www.gsrescue1.org

animal.description: All of our dogs are Spayed/Neutered, Micro-chipped, and up to date on shots before being released to adopters.The Willow situation: Willow has lived with a wonderful family for a couple of years now. She is still in need of a home who is ideal for her and her special needs but she has come a very very long way. She is deaf and has one eye, she has been through a lot of personal training, is also trained in hand signs and to use a stim collar (vibrate recall) etc.In the RIGHT situation with routine she mostly lays around all day, and is an easy bull dog 90%. She needs a home without other animals and while she absolutely loves kids, she is too strong for them at times. This may seem silly, but the problem is that while she is VERY tolerant of kids, she is also an extreme leg humper🤦🏼‍♀️.. yup! And sometimes she gets super excited and will grab onto a leg and scratch you up if you don't correct her and kiddos aren't strong enough to do this. She is very very strong. In a home with other animals she is very different- she has high drive and becomes neurotic and overstimulated and very difficult in a home with other animals. In the wrong home she can be difficult to manage so we are looking for the right situation now that we have her figured out. Crate trained, potty trained, great temperament.She thrives and requires a strong calm structure and leadership. She can be very submissive to her people but can also be pushy and dominant if you aren't managing her properly. It is hard to get her attention with her hearing special needs and loss of an eye, so her person needs to continue to work on her on e collar recall/ hand signals. She has already received lots of training. We want to ensure that her adoptive home will love and keep her for life.🐾 Go to www.k9ppr.org to send us an adoption application and tell us all about you and the home you would give sweet Willow! #k9ppr loves their bulldogs! Opt to adopt!If you you are interested in meeting one of the dogs, please fill out an application from our website at www.K9PawPrintRescue.org. We are always in need of fosters and volunteers

Looks like: Finnish Spitz Mix
Female, 10 years old, 35 pounds

Dixie Mae is a sweetheart. She can be a little nervous at first when away from her person, but she will continue to be all tail wags, happy and social. She loves people! Dixie is great in the home, good about being in a crate, and understands basic commands well. While home, she is excited for people to come over and wants all of their attention, to pet and love on her. She is good around children too. 

Dixie Mae is an active dog and loves to go for walks and hike. She would do best with an active person or active family.She does have some leash reactivity when she is out and about, so needs an adopter who is willing to work on her leash manners around other dogs. 

Dixie is house trained and very well mannered in the home. She prefers to be the only dog in the home because she attaches very quickly to her person and wants them all to herself. She is extremely intelligent, a quick learner, and eager to please. 

We will only consider a one dog household for Dixie, as we know she really prefers to be the only dog and we want to set her up for success. 

Dixie came into our program when her family was moving across the country and could not take her along.

animal.description:
Alex is a good looking pup, estimated to be 12 months old in December and we’re guessing him to be a Shepherd/Hound mix. He came to HART from a shelter in West Virginia where he was picked up as a stray. He is 15 inch tall at the shoulder, weighs 32 pounds, and has a muscular build. He was treated for worms, cleaned, got all his shots, and is doing well.  

Alex is a very playful dog, loves to play, run, and wrestle with other dogs. He is also playful with people and would be good with children, although you’d need to be careful with smaller children as he gets excited when meeting new people and may knock them over, but fine after initial meeting. He does chase cats.  He likes to explore new places, like the garage and basement, etc. He likes chasing balls and will play fetch. 

He's very loving and confident dog that likes to cuddle on the couch in your lap after some playtime. We're not sure how long Alex was fending for himself in the wild, so some basic training is likely in order. He is crate trained. Working on house training and is doing well if left out often enough.

He does come well on command, stops most of the time on command,  and working on sit command. He is very food driven. He likes to run in the yard, so a fenced yard would be best for him. Initially he pulls some during walks, but he loves all the new sites and smells.  

He’s a sweetie and would absolutely love a home to call his own!

If you would like to meet Alex, please go to our website at www.rescueahart.org and fill out an online adoption application.


All HART dogs are spayed/neutered, microchipped and up to date on all vaccines, including bordatella and rabies.   They are heartworm tested and on preventative for heartworm, fleas, and ticks.   If you are interested in any of our pets, you must complete an online dog adoption application   at www.rescueAhart.org .   The application will put you in touch with this wonderful dog's foster family so you can schedule a meeting.   Thanks!   www.rescueAhart.org

animal.description:
**To be considered for one of our dogs, please fill out the online application on https://austinbulldogrescue.com/adopt/**

BONDED WITH CHANCE

Chance and Maple are a bonded pair saved from the brink of death when they escaped from their former owner's yard and were attacked by other dogs. From what we heard, faithful Chance tried hard to protect little Maple, and we aren't surprised, given how loving he is with her and how sad he gets when she is not around. Chance and Maple are most definitely a bonded pair who need to be adopted out together. Because of their recent trauma, they can live with other dogs but introductions must be done slowly. They both LOVE any and all people and honestly believe they are each ~15lbs and can comfortably fit on your lap. Together. Chance is party animal of the two, always wanting to be in the center of the action when out and about while Maple is thrilled with pawing at the closest human hand to direct them toward given scratches. These special bullies are incredibly (and miraculously) loving, loyal, and trusting, despite having been through the worst of the worst.

BISCOTTI (male)
Breed: terrier mixAge: approx. 1 yearWeight: approx. 10 lbs.
Adopter Experience: Experience with shy/timid dogs
Status - AVAILABLE

Biscotti is a wonderful little guy once he feels safe & secure. Loud noises and high energy makes him nervous, for this reason a home with children under twelve is not ideal. Biscotti is med - low energy, loves affection and lap lounging. Ggreat with dogs and likely would be with cats although he has not been cat tested.
ADOPTION REQUIREMENTS & PROCEDURES
Mutt Match L.A. does not adopt out of state nor do we adopt on a first come first serve basis but rather to the home that is best suited for each particular dog and breed. An application, home check, contract and adoption fee are required for all adoptions. All dogs will be, or required to be, spayed/neutered, current on vaccinations and microchipped before adoption. Most of our dogs are from local LA area shelters, we generally have no prior history for them.
Adoption fees vary between $400 - $500 for puppies 8 weeks - 5 years, $350 6 - 9 years and $300 for dogs over 9 years. Adoption fee covers spay/neuter, vaccinations, microchip, wellness check and of course all the love and daily care we take with each dog before they are adopted.
We believe a well behaved dog is a happy dog and companion. Therefore, we require at least one session with one of our recommended behaviorists for a reduced fee which is not included in the adoption fee.
We are a busy fully functioning rescue and facility, unfortunately, we do not take requests for more photos and/or video. The photos you currently see are what we currently have and are updated as we recevie new photos. For additional information or questions, please email us at info@muttmatchla.org. To submit an application, please visit us at www.muttmatchla.org. Mutt Match L.A. is an all volunteer rescue, please allow at least 48 hours for a returned response of all inquires.
Thank you! We look forward to hearing from you soon.

animal.description:
Petey is an 18-month old pup who is a lovebug! He's super affectionate and enjoys being attached to his people all of the time. He really needs a family who can be home with him most of the time, as he gets scared when he's by himself. 

He's full of energy and isn't a fan of pottying on a leash, so he absolutely needs a home with a fenced yard! 

Petey has done really well with cats, and with some patience he really enjoys doggy siblings to play with. Slow introductions are needed, but once he's there the fun never stops!

Petey can be timid in unfamiliar places. He can get overwhelmed with seeing lots of people, cars going by, and finding strange smells. With some patience, a trusted human, and lots of love, he should improve with new situations.

With Petey's nervousness, it's important that if his new home has kids, that they be 10+ years old for better understanding. 

Petey needs a fenced yard, a family who can be home with him most of the time, and kids over 10 years old. He likes doggy playmates but he also prefers to hog his people to himself so other pets aren't necessary. Petey would do best with a family wants to earn his trust and patiently help him past his hurdles. If you're looking a super affectionate little bed-hog, Petey is the boy for you! 

Petey's adoption fee is 300. This fee covers the care he's received during his time with us. Petey is neutered, microchipped, just saw the vet (all clear),  and recently received his booster shots. He's definitely a good boy! 

Petey is doing well in his foster home, so he'd love to find a forever family to start 2021 off right!

While we are based in rural Minnesota, Petey is being fostered near the metro, and we complete adoptions all over the state! 

An Adoption Application must be submitted to take the next step if you are interested in meeting/adopting Petey. Please allow up to 7 business days for us to get back to you! Apply here: https://petstablished.com/adoption_form/25718/generic

animal.description:
Denali was born in January of 2020 and is a big boy - about 120 lbs.  He was rehomed from his first home due to lack of space and no fenced yard.  Although he was raised with children, he was unfortunately not treated well by them, so would do best in a home with older teenage children or an all adult home.  his 2nd home had a 5 year old child who he played too rough with, resulting in him coming into rescue.  He is friendly and playful  with other dogs, and loves to snuggle with adults.  His best match would be an energetic female dog. He does not know boundaries, so would benefit from some obedience training.  He still thinks he is a 20 lb pup! We recommend obedience training for all newly adopted pyrs, to help you create a special bond with you and your new friend, and so you have a well behaved canine. Great Pyrenees are willing to learn, but are not as eager to comply with commands as much as other breeds. They are bred to be independent thinkers. Applicants must be over 25, own their own home and all children in household must be over 15 years old. Your resident pets must be up to date on vaccines, sterilized, you must have a good history of vet care for them, and you must have used heartworm preventative year round for your dogs. 


Denali will be placed as an inside pet with outside privileges. You MUST have a securely fenced yard accessible from your home. Invisible fencing does not work with this breed and they will take the shock for the freedom.  Great Pyrenees are bred to roam and will create their own territory if not secured, which can led to them being lost, hit by vehicles or shot by people who see them as a threat. The breed is not a good off leash dog, and cannot be trusted to not run away.  A Great Pyrenees off leash is a " DisAPyr." 

If you are interested in adopting or fostering, please complete the appropriate application on our website, www.igpr.org under the Adopt tab. 

All of our dogs marked as needing foster homes are also available for adoption.  If a dog is listed on this site, it is available.  No need to contact us to see if it is,  We do require you  complete the adoption application prior to meeting a dog.

We also offer a foster to adopt program. You foster the dog, and have first right of refusal on them if an approved application is submitted for them. 

In fostering a dog, the dog comes to you fully vetted. and groomed. You provide good quality food, grooming, and we provide the heartworm preventative and medical care, if needed* .(*Based on approval from IGPR.)

Denali will be placed with a neuter agreement to be completed between when he is 18 - 24 months old.   Studies have shown that large breed dogs benefit from the hormones in their bodies to help with long bone growth, to lessen the chances of osteosarcoma or joint issues occurring later n their life.  At the time of the neuter, $100 will be refunded with proof of neuter. 

Adoption fee is $400

He is ok with other calm dogs but would probably be best if he had his own little spot. animal.description:
FROM THE FOSTER: Hello future family! My name is Maybelline, but my foster family of six months calls me Minnie. I've been told I am the sweetest girl in the world, as well as the goofiest. Although I'm quite the cutie, I had mange when I came in and my fur is still growing, and I had an eye that was damaged and needed to be removed, so Im also adjusting to life with one eye. I love my people and I am incredibly loyal. I will always be there to snuggle with you (I love warm, comfy spots to curl up in), play with you, and protect you. I am currently working on walking on a leash and my socialization with other dogs. Even though I'm unsure about some things, I'm housebroken and follow commands well. I like to run around and be silly, so I am looking to meet someone with a big yard to bounce around in! Since my previous life was a tough one, I am hoping that someone will take a chance on me, love me, and be patient with me while I continue navigating the dog world.

ORIGINAL POST: Maybelline is a 3 year old, 48 pound bulldog mix that came from a shelter in south GA. When we got her she had demodex mange and was missing most of her hair and had one eye that was damaged and had to be removed. We do not know her backstory but we cant imagine that it was a life well-lived. Thats all over with now. She has been in the program for a few months with a wonderful foster, while she recuperated and now she is ready to go to a forever home. She is incredibly loyal and loving, great in the house, walks well on a leash and follows commands. We have kept her close the past few months while she went thru two surgeries, so she needs a little socialization with other dogs, which we will do, but we would love to get her adopted, so she can start her new life. If you would like to adopt this sweet girl. Please go to www.atlantalabrescue.com to fill out an application.

animal.description: Hi hi hi!! Nice to meet you guys, my names Monroe. Pretty name right? Just like me. : When I first arrived here I was so scared and unsure of everything. I came off a little mean, but staff saw right through my bluff! They gave me the time I needed to adjust, and my personality started showing! I do pull on leash so I would recommend leash training for me. I love to be around my humans, but I get SOO hyper!! I do what they call, zoomies, although in the process I may run into you! No harm done, just excitement! I tolerate all handling but I become so excited so I cannot stay still. I may come off a bit rude when it comes to play time, because I love to jump and I may jump too hard, I don't mean it! I'm just too excited. I love treats and rawhide, I don't mind sharing either. So, since I am a queen (duh) I need to be respected by other dogs! I met a energetic invasive male who I met nicely, but he became a little rude so I corrected him! Being that this is who I am, I would recommend a family with children no younger than 12 due to my jumpiness and high arousal, also initial meetings. I hope to meet the perfect family soon!

animal.description:
Buddy the firedog is 11 years old and 14 lbs of sweet love. 

As an older gentleman he has limited vision and hearing, but with time to get used to his home he navigates well! He also takes daily medication for his heart, but this guy doesn’t let his challenges stop him from getting lots of cuddles!

Buddy does well with respectful kids who understand how to approach a vision challenged dog, and gets along with dogs of all sizes as long as they give him time to get used to them!

Buddy walks well on a leash for short walks, does great with house training as long as his people let him out regularly, and sleeps through the night like the gentleman he is!

He is neutered, UTD on shots, HW neg and on HW prevention.

His adoption donation is $250.00.

If you are interested in the above dog, please do not email us and tell us that you are interested, but submit an adoption application. The link for the application is below.

To submit an application go here……chihuahua-rescue.com/adoption-application/
An application must be submitted and approved before a meet-n-greet can be scheduled.

Your current dogs/cats must be spayed or neutered unless a veterinarian has determined that your current pet(s) should not be fixed due to medical reasons. 

They must also be up-to-date on shots and on HW preventative.
Reference checks and a home visit are required so SE dogs can only be adopted in NC/SC, VA, TN, AL, MD and GA.

animal.description:
Lt Dan T. is an 11-year-old male German Shepherd Dog who was found stray in Southern California. He is a handsome, confident boy who greets people with kisses. He is house trained, loves to be petted and rides well in the car. Lt Dan is active and playful with wonderful manners and a loving personality! He was obviously part of a loving family that lost track of him or could no longer keep him in these hard times. Lt Dan knows basic obedience commands and hand signals. He is crate trained and shows no food aggression or other difficult behaviors. Lt Dan will make a great addition to a new family!

Lt Dan T. Summary:
- Lt Dan is a male, 11 yrs old, weighs 80 lbs, current on shots
- Good with Adults, children, dogs, and travel in the car
- Cats TBD

Lt Dan passed a set of evaluation tests before being accepted into the TSGSR. The tests are not intended to assess how smart the dog is but are important for TSGSR to determine if the dog is expected to be safe in a family home. The tested behaviors check to see if the dog will guard or protect food or toys from people, will tolerate handling all over its body (including ears, nose, lips to check teeth, lifting paws, belly, back, and gently pulling the tail) and the ability to get along with other well behaved dogs. He remained calm during all of these tests and showed no aggressive tendencies. 

Please join us in welcoming Lt Dan to TSGSR! Check back often. We will be updating his bio as we learn more about him!

What's Next for Lt Dan T:
Thulani Senior German Shepherd Rescue (TSGSR) will continue to see that Lt Dan is well cared for and receives all medical care needed for his well being while in our care. In addition, TSGSR is beginning a search for an adoptive home that will care for him for the rest of his life. He will come to his new home with a supply of food, a cushy pad if wanted, and other goodies such as toys. 

Lt Dans medical expenses will be covered for the rest of his life by Thulani Senior German Shepherd Rescue (TSGSR)!

If you want to learn more about Lt Dan, or are interested in possibly providing an adoptive or foster home, please send us a message by clicking on the "Ask About Me" button. We will often get feedback or "updates" from a dog's foster home and as any updates become available they will be included here.

If you are reading about him on Petfinder.com sometimes an available YouTube video is not listed. If this occurs you can still view the video by pasting its URL into a new browser window or tab.

Available Video URL(s): https://youtu.be/OMf-KeehU9Y

Saving one dog wont change the world. It will change the world for that one dog.

animal.description: Hi, my name is Cheyenne! I’m a small size Great Pyrenees mix and weigh about 65 lbs. I am about 3 years old and originally from New Mexico. I’m very friendly but very shy and easily startled in the beginning with people. I get along great with other dogs, and am good with cats and other critters as well. I am a low to medium energy dog and am house trained. I love to go for walks and walk very well on a leash. I do not like riding in the car at all and am stressed out when I have to go somewhere. If you are looking for a dog to go places with, I am NOT your girl. I much prefer to stay around my home. It helps to have another dog with me when I have to go somewhere but I still get very worried. At night I like to sleep in a crate with the door open. I love chew toys like antlers and benebones. I am a picky eater, and sometimes skip meals. I am working on some separation anxiety issues, especially when the sun is down. I am afraid of strangers, visitors to the house, and cars. When I am afraid I bark to warn them off and can remain stressed and upset even after they are gone. I’m a fan of open spaces, but not of living in town and human activity. I’m therefore looking for a rural or mountain home where there are fewer things that scare me. I will be the happiest in a home with at least one other dog. I was used to living in a pack and I feel more confident when there are other dogs around. I am a sweet and affectionate dog, looking for a patient family that will give me a home for life. Apply at fromforgottentoforever.com/adoptionapplication/.

animal.description:
You can fill out an adoption application online on our official website.Simba is a 3 year old Presa Canario. He is a very energetic and playful guy who is always down for belly rubs and neck scratches. Cuddling is new to him so he is very awkward, but he loves it and now even gives little kisses. Toys! He is obsessed with toys, all toys, but especially if they have stuffing that he can rip out. He loves to be with his people and will follow you anywhere except the basement, waaay too scary for him. Simba is housebroken and somewhat crate trained. He is a great dog and highly trainable, he would do fantastic with more training. He is a guardian breed and will do best in an experienced home. He also has a high prey drive. No children, no cats, no small animals.
Simba was found Feb/March 2020 in Michigan. His microchip said that he was missing for 2 months from Miami, Florida! We tried for months to return him to his owners, but the pandemic made things difficult. His owners could not afford to bring him home and signed him over to me to find him a new home. He is HW positive and is currently going through treatment.
He is available to be fostered or placed in a foster to adopt home. He will have to be kept calm during his heart worm treatment.

animal.description:
Start your New Year with this Sweetheart! Twila is loving, energetic, cuddly and smart. Maybe lab/pitbull/shar pei with a whippet tail and a hound focus on scent, she’s about 4 years old and came to us as an owner release. 

Twila is housetrained, well-mannered and responsive to her people. She will come when called indoors and in the yard. She knows basic commands and will sit and wait nicely for meals. She hasn’t had much training on leash walking, but her foster family has been working with her on it. 

She’s a smart girl who needs as much mental stimulation as physical. She loves her explorations in the woods at the off-leash dog park and socializes well with the other dogs.  Sometimes she gets a little rough when she starts to get tired or overstimulated. When she does, she just needs a little help getting grounded again.

She would enjoy continued training in a positive method training class and would do well in agility and/or scent training. Twila would love to have a home with a big yard where she can play and romp. She’d be an enthusiastic hiking and beachcombing companion. An active family who wants to include her in their outings, activities and adventures would be ideal.

She would be happy with another well-adjusted dog in the family but isn’t a good match for cats. We think the best fit would be with adults or a family with children who are dog savvy.

Twila has a big heart and just wants someone to love, someone to play with her, cuddle with her, and love her back. She's looking for a home where she is adored and made to feel special. She’ll make you feel special, too!

Twila’s adoption fee includes spay/neuter, basic vaccinations, rabies vaccination, and heartworm tested negative.

You can find her application here:

https://forms.gle/5eSBjHrWv7pTEEzUA

Questions? Contact us at connellpetrescue@gmail.com 

Thank you! And Twila thanks you!

animal.description:
Blue von Bexbach is a gorgeous 9 month old Husky mixed with white Teddy Bear.  His baby blues and rounded ears make you want to scoop him up for a cuddle, easy to do considering his smaller size of 30 pounds.  Cute and sweet, Blue likes you giving him ear and belly rubs, and will lean on you for attention if you wait too long.  Just seeing you starts his tail wagging and his face smiling.  Our mid-energy guy walks well in a pack of dogs, responding quickly to any needed corrections, and growling if another dog gets too close.  We are working to socialize Blue more around other dogs; for now, he should be the only fur-ball in your home.  Blue has a condition called mega-esophagus, readily managed by having him eat and drink in an upright position using a Bailey chair – kind of a high chair for dogs (the rescue can provide this chair).  He enthusiastically puts himself in it, standing with his paws on the tray, waiting to be served. Think of how perfect he’ll look at the end of your bed or in the back of your car!

Westside dog Biographies, availability and new photos are updated regularly on our website! So, check in and log on often! 

Westside thanks you for looking at our amazing dogs and for choosing to save an animal's life through rescue. 

Don't forget to visit your local animal shelter...the source of many of our dogs.
 
www.sheprescue.org

https://www.facebook.com/WGSRescue

animal.description:
Norman is an active 7 year old male Bench English Setter. His owner died a few months ago and the wife is unable to give him the exercise he needs due to her physical disability.

Norman would do best with a male owner and possibly another same size active dog. Since Norman lost his male owner (and much needed exercise) he has started bullying and thus intimidating the other older English Setter in the household. So he will do best in a home with an active man who can provide leadership and daily exercise and training.

Norman is leash reactive (lunges and barks) at other dogs when out walking. He is very strong and would require experienced and consistent training in this area.

He is used to a quiet home where someone was home most of the time with no children or smaller pets and is looking for a similar type home. He has never lived with cats and is not a candidate for a home with cats.

He is house trained and when inside he is happy to lay on the couch and loves to have his head in your lap. Furniture privileges are very important for Norman. He does bark if he sees activity outside the window, but otherwise he is calm inside when he has plenty of outside exercise and stimulation.

Outside Norman is active for a middle aged bench boy and requires a home with a secure fenced (at least 4 feet tall) yard that is large enough to run and interesting to explore. He is used to daily walks and would like this in his new home too.

Norman is neutered, up to date on vaccines and tests, and microchipped. He is in a home in Denver, CO.

 For an application to adopt or for more information about Southwest English Setter Rescue including our adoption requirements and transport availability, please go to http://www.swesr.org/. Please call us at 214-997-3885 if you have any questions.

animal.description:
From Marley's family..

This beautiful boy needs a new home! His owner is having health problems and can no longer work or train Marley to be the brilliant dog he is meant to be. Marley is approximately 2 years old and weighs 90 lbs.  If you are someone that loves to run/walk or hike then you will enjoy this dog! Marley is very curious and active; he is an amazing swimmer and likes to spend hours in the water! He also loves to ride in the car!!
 
Although Marley is good with kids and dogs we do not want him to go to a home that has children and dogs at this time. Marley has been ignored and needs undivided attention. He can be around other dogs and children in the future after trained but at this time he should be with someone who focuses on him! He is so smart, learns very quickly so physical exercise and consistent training will get the job done quickly. Marley is housetrained, good in the car, medium energy and will return what you give. 
 
Marley has been working with an amazing trainer who believes so much in him she is willing to offer some free training if you are invested and willing to put the work in. Please see her comments below!

From welcome Home Sanctuary... This dog and trainer below is a gift. If you have the opportunity to work with this respected trainer you will learn more about dogs and training then you ever thought possible, it's a win win. Sarah is offering her free time for this dog because she believes in him that much. We will be waiving the $365 fee and asking that it is given to Sarah before you bring Marley home. You will not be able to adopt unless you make a commitment to training with Sarah...

Marley’s trainer here:
 
Marley is an exceptional dog, in need of an exceptional home.
 
In several decades of in-depth and full-time involvement in the training and behavior community, including two decades as a professional animal behavior expert seeing and working with canine behavior from pretty much every angle, I have seen few dogs with Marley’s potential.
 
I’ve seen and trained many dogs who have become regarded as the “ultimate” in canine behavior and training, fitting a wide variety of needs and desires from service dog to competitor. And always most importantly, loving companion and canine ambassador. And yet, Marley’s potential still stands out, even from the perspective of such a depth and breadth of experience.
 
Marley is highly intelligent and perceptive. And, just as critical to the ease of teaching and living with a dog, Marley’s intelligence is naturally and easily focused on cooperation and teamwork. With the right methods, he is excellent at learning whatever we wish him to learn, and then doing that to the best of his considerable abilities.
 
He is also outstandingly athletic. He loves to play, is an amazing swimmer, and has beautiful natural balance, coordination, and body awareness.
 
I would eagerly take him home in a heartbeat, if I could justify bringing one more dog home at this time, without risking running out of the time and resources for my current dogs. And I would do so knowing, without question, that Marley would make me proud, as a role model and helpmate in my work as a canine professional. If I could bring one more dog home at this time, any dog at all, it would without question be Marley. That is how amazing he is.
 
However, as happens to exceptional dogs like Marley just as often as it happens to any other dog, the humans on whom Marley depended in his early life, were not the right match for him. Eventually, he was given to a well-intentioned person who simply did not have the resources to care for another dog, let alone one who is large, young, athletic, and energetic. Additionally, despite Marley being as brilliant and willing as a dog could be, he was handed off to his current owner with both a lack of what he should have been given by that time in his life, and some residual issues as a result of all that he had been through before coming to his current home.
 
Even so, once we began our work together, things were improving as well and as rapidly as one could have hoped for. Until a significant life event occurred for his owner, which made continuing that work or even taking care of Marley’s basic needs, (exercise, training, attention), simply impossible. 
 
Marley blossomed with the right training techniques — from our first lesson together, he rewarded even the highest expectations, at every turn. Despite very little time to dedicate to his training, to exercising him, to socializing him, he nonetheless showed up for each lesson by not just meeting that high standard of expectations, but more often exceeding them than not.
 
Unfortunately, he has not been able to have training for a while now, due to a lack of resources. And without that, as well as without time to exercise him or care for him, the home in which he lives cannot keep him. There is simply no space, no time, and no resources to make that work.
 
Because Marley is so exceptional, and because his response has been so reliably outstanding, to the specific techniques I have developed over the past 30 years of intensive involvement in animal behavior, I am offering something I have offered to only one other exceptional dog in the past. (And, by the way, that dog went from being deemed “hopeless”, due to improper training techniques, to becoming the “best dog” his very experienced owners feel they have ever had. And Marley has the abundant ability become that once-in-a-lifetime dog, for the right home, as well.)
 
What I am offering is this: For the right foster home, or adopter, or foster-to-adopt, I will give weekly lessons at no cost. This is a commitment which, if taken, must be taken as seriously as if it is being dearly bought; because the goal is for Marley to reach his marvelous potential, and he has already paid too high a price, for people to play around with his training without consistency or sufficient knowledge.
 
For someone who wants to learn more about canine behavior and training, wants to learn how to do a better job of fostering, or training, or simply caring for their own dogs, this is an opportunity to gain literally thousands of dollars’ worth of education. All while saving an amazing dog, and potentially adopting the dog of your dreams, if the fit is right. A potential lifelong win for his foster, his adopter, for the person who now owns him but truly cannot keep him, and most of all, for this magnificent and deserving at-risk dog.

Welcome Home Sanctaury is asking you, his new adopter continue his education so that Marley can thrive.

This is a courtesy post for all who care and love Marley.

animal.description:
Roy

Roy is a large neutered male senior Coonhound mix who is about 10 to 12 years old and weighs about 70 pounds.

He was found as a stray and sadly was never claimed. He's super sweet, friendly, and social. Roy always wants to meet other dogs and people he sees on his walks, which he looks forward to greatly. Although he can have bursts of energy, especially for a dog his age, he also very much enjoys his naps.

Roy has a big howl on him and will let other dogs know when they pass by. However, when meeting dogs he knows, they can bark at him and he just stares quietly back.

When out on walks, Roy can sometimes pull toward interesting things he wants to investigate, but he has made good progress with his leash training. He may rush in and sniff dogs (which can be an issue for some dogs), but once he ha a sniff he minds his business and carries on.

Roy doesn't appear to have had much training in the past, but he's a great guy and is willing to learn. He is fully housetrained and is also very good in a car (he came all the way from the Ottawa area).

Roy needs a house with a fenced yard; committed adopters and a family that will love him unconditionally for the rest of his days!

Medical: he's had a dental, several lumps removed (all benign), he has a LOW GRADE heart murmur that was ex-rayed and NOT enlarged (no meds required) and tested positive for LYME which he was treated for and is NOT symptomatic (needs to have a retest in June and only 5% of dogs who test positive ever show signs of Lyme; so it's not like human form of Lyme's disease)

He's neutered, up-to-date with vaccines, chipped, all his blood work for organ function is NORMAL and he's HW negative

Can you give this sweet, friendly boy the forever home full of the love and care he needs? He'll pay you back with Coonhound howls and wags!

This guy really deserves a break and needs good dog people to swoop him up and love him as much as he'll love you!

More about Roy

House trained Friendly with people Color: Black and White Activity level: Active at times with down time Very little training

animal.description:
Sweet as “Honey”...... Honey is looking for her forever home. Her dad is in the military and unfortunately is still deployed and can’t care for her.  She has been in boarding for several months in hopes her dad would be able to come back for her, but he is unable to do that. She needs a new family that can spend time with her and love her.   

Dogs laugh, but they laugh with their tails. -
Max Eastman

Honey 

She’s a “in your face” kind of dog. She needs to be reminded “not” to jump up. She’s getting better, but she just wants your attention and will jump to do that. A little more training should do the trick. She comes when called. She’s very food and treat motivated. 
She loves her Nyla bone and is comfortable in her crate, but might chew up her bedding, if she gets bored. 
She loves to be outside to run and play.
She will need supervised introductions to other dogs her size. She wouldn’t do well with small dogs or cats. 
A passive non-aggressive male would be her best match.

Adoption Process: In order to adopt, we require an adoption application. After you submit an application, if you pass the screening, we will contact you to schedule a phone interview. We will call your references, including your veterinarian and landlord (when appropriate). We will also conduct a home visit. After these steps are complete, you will be approved to adopt a dog. Please note this process takes 1-2 weeks so applications submitted when you are ready to bring a dog home within that time frame. You can meet our adoptable dogs at events, however, we cannot guarantee that dogs at events do not have pre-approved applicants meeting them there as well, so the application is the best way to start the process.

Mission Statement: Forever true to "The Underdog", Rural Dog Rescue is dedicated to saving the lives of dogs in shelters who are often overlooked for adoption or rescue. We save the dogs who are at most risk of being euthanized: the hounds, the black dogs, the seniors, the sick and the broken. We make a commitment to reserve a minimum of 50% of the dogs we save to The Underdog. Root For The Underdog!

Rural Dog Rescue's home base is in Washington, DC. We adopt to the Washington, DC metropolitan area to include Maryland and Northern Virginia.

We support several high kill shelters that euthanize in 72 hours and whose kill rate is 70% or higher in rural areas of Virginia, West Virginia, North and South Carolina. Rural Dog Rescue also helps dogs in need in Washington, DC and Maryland.

We are 100% volunteer and foster based and no salaries are paid. 100% of your donation and adoption fee goes to helping the dogs and cats of Rural Dog Rescue.

Although we try to be as accurate as possible, Rural Dog Rescue cannot guarantee the breed or full-grown adult size of any of the dogs or puppies in its care. Because many of these dogs were found as strays or are the result of irresponsible, unplanned breeding, we do not know the dog's exact background and can only list breed and size by our best educated guess. If exact breed and size are important to you, please consider adopting a dog from a specific breed rescue. Our goal is for our dogs to be adopted by people who will love and care for them forever for who they are - no matter what breed and size they turn out to be!

All dogs go to their new homes spayed or neutered, up to date on all shots, dewormed (although a second deworming may be required), started on heartworm and flea and tick preventative and sometimes microchipped.

animal.description:
Meet AVA...
We pulled Ava years ago from a kill shelter and it took a while until she found a home. She was adopted by a couple but 4 years later, on Christmas Eve,  the husband brought her back in tears fearing for the safety of his dog. He saw a disturbing video on his security footage of his wife beating trees with a long stick along the fence line and harassing the dogs with it as well. Another video showed how she got the dogs all hyped up and when they started fighting each other she just sat there completely spaced out. The husband realized he can't reason with an addict and the had to choose safety for his dogs.
We would love for this girl not to grow old in rescue care. 
She would love a home where she can be the only dog just because of what she has been through. She is not dog aggressive but developed an attitude she shows sometimes. 
She loves to go for a stroll and is not requiring lots of exercise. She loves to snuggle and is very well behaved, crate and house trained. She loves people and kids and is a very gentle older girl 
Ava is about 7 years old and might have some bull terrier in her.
She has only 1 eye and we don't know what happened. She might not be the most prettiest dog in some people eyes but she is the most beauty at heart and loyal to the bone. This girl will melt your heart if you give her a chance.

If you would like to meet our amazing Ava, please send us a message in order to receive an application. We are only able to meet with approved applicants by appointment.

Ava's adoption fee is $ 250 which includes all vaccines, heartworm test, spay and micro chip.

All dogs go to their new homes spayed or neutered, up to date on all shots, dewormed (although a second deworming may be required), started on heartworm and flea and tick preventative and sometimes microchipped.

animal.description:
Oh Holly, our sweet Christmas hound. She was in a tiny rural shelter in OK and they reached out for help because she went into labor there. A cold concrete floor is no place for newborn puppies. Holly is 80lbs and the best mama to her 4 newborn babies.

Holly was terrified of the leash and had never worn a collar in her life before she came to us. In a short week she has progressed to confidently walking on leash with our dogs for support and takes his time taking in all the smells.  With lots of treats and love she conquered his fear of the harness and stairs in just a few short hours. She is very treat motivated and is learning quickly how good life could be.

She is super sweet. She loves both food and attention a lot. She likes to sleep on her bed in between walks, meal times and cuddles. She gets super excited when she thinks it is going out time.  She settles down when you sit on the couch or leave the room. She does well in her room wiith her puppies.

She sometimes shows her dissatisfaction by sounding like a motor bike and short barks she stops upon hearing her name. We have learned that a Kong toy full of frozen food and PB makes her enjoy her night time routine more. Treats and a happy voice always gets her attention too. She LOVES chasing squirrels if given the chance. She still does not show any interest in toys, and her main interest in fenced areas are sniffing around. However, she has recently learned to play fetch with a stick. She responds to her name and comes back to you for some pets or treats. She does well in bath time. Generally, she is super sweet and patient with her people. She is a great loving companion dog.

Amazing Grace was found as a stray, filthy, dejected, and in rough shape. We were stunned to find out she does not have any major health issues, except some aging joints and loss of hearing. She is, in fact, deaf, but it sure doesn't slow her down one bit. Grace adores her humans and isn't afraid to express herself with her walrus-y barks and howls when there's something she wants. She also has the most hilarious single snaggle tooth that sticks out of her underbite at all times. Amazing Grace is in a foster home currently with other dogs, and generally ignores both them and the resident kitties. She is also perfectly happy nested in a fluffy dog bed or by your side for a snuggle. Since Grace is deaf, she will take some time to adjust to her new surroundings and might get a little grumbly if she's startled. For that reason, we think she'd do best in a home without a ton of visitors or small children (visiting or living in the home) so that she can feel comfortable in her space.

animal.description:
LAWRENCEVILLE, GA

Gordo is a 7 year old Pekinese mix we pulled from a high kill shelter His chances where slim to leave the shelter alive due to his attitude problem.
Gordo was an owner surrender to the shelter and the previous owner sad, he just doesn't like to be petted....

Well.... let me explain....!

READ CAREFULLY:

Once you bonded with Gordo yo can pet and cuddle him. He will let you brush him, he likes to go for walks, rides well in the car and does great with other dogs and cats. He is almost house broken and loves to hang out on the couch with you . Gordo likes to have a routine. 

Here comes the BUT.... you will have to go through a process with him so he opens up to you and until then he can be ugly sometimes. He grummels and growls... will bit you if you try to touch him to soon. He does not like to be picked up.
The way you get to him is to take him home, give him 48 hours and let him come to you. Don't force yourself on him. He will come.....He will even come and sit on your lap and snuggle up but it's all on his terms. He will not bite without warning but you have to listen to him telling you.

Gordo would love a low traffic home with no small children. If any then teenagers will be good. A single person or a couple, maybe even older, who are not looking for an active dog. Some rounds through the yard or a small stroll through the neighborhood will do it for Gordo. 
His vision is very slightly impaired which is normal for that type of dog when they get older, but it doesn't hinder him from anything. He is otherwise in perfect health.

If you would like to meet our grouchy Gremlin looking cutie, please send us a message in order to receive an application.
We only meet with approved applicants by appointment. 

Gordo's adoption fee is $ 250 which includes all vaccines, heartworm test, neuter and micro chip

animal.description:
If you are interested in any of the dogs available at New Leash Rescue, you can reach out to the foster listed below for more information and then complete an adoption application which can be found at https://www.newleashrescue.org/adopt/policy.  Please email the completed application to newleashrescue2018@gmail.com

Gracie May is a Shepherd mix that is about 2 years old. She weighs around 55 pounds, and came to us from a shelter where she had been surrendered by her family.  She was a great dog 95% of the time, but they were having some trouble when it came to her food and treats - she was being protective of resources including with people.    

Gracie can be active and playful and she loves to be outside.  She has been able to jump a 3 foot fence, so odds are she could probably also jump a 4 foot fence and would do best with a 5 or 6 foot fence where she can romp and lounge outside (even in the snow) and be safe.    Gracie gets a little anxious when a house gets too busy, so a quieter environment would be a better fit for her.

In her foster home, Gracie is good with the other dogs.  She is around other dogs 20 pounds and up.   She has played some chase but hasn't shown much interest in toys yet while she has her doggie pals around.    She doesn't care too much for puppies or younger dogs that want to be in her face.  Gracie wants to have her own space.    No cats or other small pets for Gracie in her new home. 

Gracie can be a little picky about her food and likes to have some soft food mixed in.   In her foster home, she eats in her kennel and has been doing pretty good with it.  There are not high value treats given when the dogs in the house are around each other.   Due to the prior home history and the potential for concerns with food/treats - we would not recommend Gracie for living in a home with kids under age 8.  Any children in a new home would need to be able to respect Gracie's space, especially when it comes to food.    She does great in a plastic crate in her foster home, so it's easy to put her in the crate when needed.

Gracie will shed, so needs a family that will brush her to keep that pretty fur from getting tangled.  

Adoption fee is $350.00 + tax (no checks)

Foster to contact Katie @  kit_n_caboodle22@hotmail.com

This dog will be at our adoption event at the Woodbury PetSmart on Saturday from 11-2 looking for a home!


Our fosters do the best they can to provide all information about the animal's background and temperament while in foster care in their home. An adopters routine and home environment is likely going to be different than that in their foster home. Sometimes there is more that comes out about a dog's personality once they have been able to settle in a home and truly become comfortable. 

There are great articles out there written about the different stages a pet goes through after adoption, discussing transitions that happen at 3 days, 3 weeks, and 3 months. We highly recommend reading about this - it will help you understand the transition your new pet goes through.

Livvy is a scrappy young lady from a littler of 10! Mama and babies were found under a mobile home in northeast Houston and brought into our rescue. Livvy is bold and adventurous. She loves to explore! She also loves to climb into you lap for a snuggle. She already knows how to sit on command and is working hard on house training and crate training! Make this beautiful, sweet girl part of your family!

Livvy is in a foster home with other dogs that she does well with.

Please consider making this adorable girl a member of your family and contact us to arrange to meet her. More information about the adoption process and an adoption application can be found at https://almosthomepetrescue.org. An application form can be found on the website: https://almosthomepetrescue.org/apply-now-1 and is required to be approved for any meet and greet and adoption as Almost Home Pet Rescue is a foster based rescue.

animal.description:
Hello, I am Bubba! I am a great dog! I love the water and I'm a good swimmer. If you are a water person we will get along swimmingly! I will retrieve a ball from the lake endlessly. If you bounce a ball on the sidewalk, I will jump up in the air to catch it. I'm not super keen on giving the ball back right away, because I just had so much fun catching it! But we can work out that part together. 

People who know me well think I would make a great addition to a family with children. I am very gentle and loyal. I'm also a good watchdog as I'll bark to notify my family of visitors, but then I'll welcome our visitors when my family lets me know we are all friends. 

 In the past, I've gone through service dog training together with my previous owner.  I was top of my class, probably because I have such a friendly and calm disposition. To balance out all of the amazing qualities I have, you should also know that I have a penchant for adventure and have actually gotten out of a fenced yard to go explore and meet the neighbor dogs. Obviously this is a safety hazard for me, so I really should have a tall fence to keep me safe and sound with my new family.

I am a loving and affectionate boy who is ready to start the next chapter of my life with my new family. Are you the family for me? Come meet me soon to find out. Love, Bubba

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- Intake Date: 13 Dec 2020 ----- Date of Birth: July 22, 2018 ----- Breed: Belgian Tervuren Shephard / West German Shepherd ----- Size: 75 lbs ----- Status: owner surrender ----- Compatible with: Children, dogs. NO CATS ----- Suitable for: home with a securely fenced yard. Non negotiable----- Medical/Behavioral Needs: Rehab case. 
 Little interaction and socializing outside of the home.  Fearful of new people, growly, standoffish. ----- Additional Notes: Bubba is a beauty.  He is NOT good with cats but seems great with everyone else so far.  Due to his size and not knowing how much exposure to small dogs, would recommend him for a home with medium dogs or larger.  His was purchased by a younger kid and he bred her and kept a puppy back.  Unfortunately, Bubba missed out on proper socializing and training. animal.description:
Twist would make a great companion for a curious minded person, who enjoys daily outings.  If you enjoy paying attention to everything around you, Twist has that in common with you.

She was born October 14, 2020 to a Poodle mom and a Pug dad.  She is crate trained, ready and willing to continue her leash training since she likes getting outside.  

Twist is a warm, gentle, and playful puppy.  Some of her siblings have very high energy while Twist has middle of the road type energy.

She gets along with other dogs and people, but we don't know about cats because there are not any in her foster home.

The litter was surrendered because the family could not afford the care.  Our rescue group vetted the parents, including sterilizing them, of course.


*.  *.   *.  *.  *.   *.  *.  *.   *.  *.  *.   *.  *.  *.   *.  *.  *.   *.  *.  *.   *.  *.  *.   *.  *.  *.   *.  *.  *.   *.  

We do not complete DNA tests on our rescued pups. If we do not know who the mom or dad is for sure, we guess; we use Gozer, a iPhone dog breed identifier. And, we look at their paws, ears, snout, coloring, and body build. Sometimes we are not spot on. And, remember too that even if you know the supposed dominant breed in your new puppy or adult dog, it does not mean that those particular genes will dominate your dog's personality. :)

APPLICATIONS ARE ONLINE @ karmicrescue.org

He can be very playful and LOVES to cuddle with them (no matter how they feel about it)! Spook has just started to show interest in tennis balls and other toys.

Spook will not go to an apartment. He is working on leash training, but he MUST have a fenced yard. 

His adoption fee is $150 and comes with vaccinations, microchip and neuter.

Their owners must move into a relative's home where there are already two large dogs so they need to come to us to find a new life.  Who are these two?  The girl, on the right, is a pudge.  She is a Golden/German Shepherd mix and she weighs about a hundred pounds!  Getting her down to a more svelte figure will be very good for her.  She is 8 years old.  The boy is a Golden/Lab cross.  He's 7 years old and is no tiny dog at 85 lbs.  Both are great with other dogs and with kids. (We got photos of both dogs with toddlers crawling all over them!). They haven't been around cats so we don't know their reaction.  They are bonded to one another and will need to find a foster home that can look after both of them until they are adopted into the same home.

She is a happy, friendly girl who loves people of all ages and will need a securely fenced yard and a resident dog to model appropriate canine behavior.  Lily is learning to walk on a leash and play with toys and is house trained when kept on a schedule..

Adoption donation for Lily is $400 which goes toward the high cost of veterinary care for our rescue dogs.

Wag N Train Terrier Rescue adopts to applicants living outside our geographical area as long as we are able to find a volunteer able to perform the required home visit.  If approved, the applicant is required to travel to Omaha, NE to pick up their newly adopted dog.  We do not arrange transport, or fly our rescue dogs without a human "pet nanny".  All of our dogs coming from a commercial breeding background require a securely fenced yard AND a resident dog as a companion unless stated otherwise in the dog's bio.  Please note, invisible or underground fencing is not considered secure or appropriate containment.  Adoption applications can be found at www.wagntrainterrierrescue.com/adoption-information

animal.description:
Wow! This boy is very handsome! Say hello to Patrick! <3

"Patrick Mahomes is a little skittish and shy at first, but he has really opened up this past week with us. He is such a sweet, gentle dog. He is a sensitive soul, and it is easy to forget he is a dog-he seems very much like a person! He looks like an Akbash, but could be a pyr/lab mix. Whatever his breeds, he has double dew claws, a soft, fluffy white medium length coat and the curliest white tail. He weighs around 86 pounds, and is a little underweight. He'll be a bit closer to 100 pounds ideally. Patrick's favorite activities are spending time with his people (this is his FAVORITE activity), and exploring the backyard. He loves watching for squirrels! He is a giant puppy, and will lope around the yard when he's excited-it is super cute to see! He is such a sweetheart. He enjoys watching movies with his family, and will occasionally step onto the couch for snuggles. He is a real gem, and his future family is going to luck out with him. He is such a nice dog!"

Good Afternoon folks, what a pleasure it is to meet all of you! My name is Patrick Mahomes, and I am a year old male Great Pyrenees mix. I am either mixed with Akbash or Labrador Retriever. I am a very handsome boy that will top out close to 100lbs. I was found just wandering around. After serving my stray hold and being unreclaimed I came into this pawtastic rescue! I am now ready to find my forever family and am very excited! 

MY PERSONALITY: 
I am laid back and calm, but still a giant puppy. I can get pretty playful with the other dogs. I love to romp around outside! It is pretty cute to watch me having fun. I am shy when meeting new people. I love people, but may back away or act a little nervous when I first meet someone. I haven't been to many public settings but did great with a picnic in my fosters backyard. I am shy, so will act a little cautious at first, but then I am all about getting pet! I am uninterested in playing fetch. I prefer spending my time watching for squirrels with my fosters dog, Harry. I don't seem to be much of a water dog. I have picked up some stuffed toys, and carried them around a bit. I think I'll start to play with toys as I settle in. I do great in the car, but am pretty scared of getting into the car. I am pretty scared on the leash. I am shy and can be pretty stubborn. My fosters have been working on getting me more used to a leash, but my new family will need to keep working with me. When I get scared, I will lay down. I am great with other dogs. Since I am pretty shy, it takes me a bit to realize the other dogs aren't going to hurt me. Once I feel safe, I will play all over the yard with the dogs! I have not been around any cats. I think I would do well with kids, but they will need to be patient and understanding about me being a shy dog. Loud noises and sudden movements scare me, so if I am around really active kids, I may "hide" behind a door or piece of furniture.

MY HOUSE MANNERS:
I can be trusted with the full run of the house. I am not much of a chewer. I love milk bones, oinkies, and dog treats, but haven't been interested in nylabones or rawhide rolls. I haven't shown any signs of having food aggression or resource guarding. Occasionally, I will jump up to give my fosters dad some hugs, but am not really jumpy. I do believe I would do good in an apartment setting, IF my new owner is okay with working with me on my leash training. I am not a big barker, but will bark if I hear something suspicious all of a sudden. I am protective of my family and a guardian, after all. I have free roam of the house when my fosters are away. At night, I sleep in the bedroom. I would prefer being on the bed, but Shade and Harry(my fosters dogs) are pretty bossy about the bed being theirs! I would love to sleep close to my people, though. I am potty trained, but not kennel trained. 

To my new family: 
Here are the things that I am looking for in my new family! 

-I am a very easy going dog, and am all about being with my family. I think I would do well with just about any family. I would enjoy doing activities like walks and car rides (once I warm up and understand I am safe). I would also do well in a calmer household too. I'd be a GREAT work from home dog-I won't interrupt any conference calls, and would like to nap next to my human. I get along with dogs, so I'd do well with another dog. I really prefer being with my people, so would do well as an only dog, too.

Sooo....if you give me your hand, I will give you my paw! And from there, we will start an amazing new journey...TOGETHER! Apply for me at https://www.pyrpawsandfluffytailsrescue.com/adoption-app 

My adoption fee is $225. That includes my DHLPP, Rabies, and Bordatella shots. I will be micro-chipped, heart-worm tested, ehrlichia tested, have a fecal done, be de-wormed, be spayed/neutered and will be current on my heart-worm and flea/tick prevention.

Lastly, I am being fostered in Tulsa, OK. I have no qualms about going out of state if my adopters don't live in Oklahoma. All I ask is they come pick me up. Those transports are too stressful and this rescue doesn't put us on those or ship us.
