animal.description:
Meet WILLOW! She is ready for her forever family! 

This beautiful lab/beagle/cute mix is other dog friendly and is about 5-6 years old. She was found on the streets of Arkansas before being rescued. Willow's foster mom reports that she uses doggy doors to use the bathroom and loves being on the couch. Like with every dog we recommend following a two week shutdown to help ensure success in your adoption. 

Other information from her foster: Willow would be happiest in a home  where someone is home more then not. She does need a fenced in yard and doggy doors is ideal so if she starts feeling anxious she can go outside and not feel so "cooped up". She needs a family who understand that rescue dogs need time to decompress to ensure a successful adoption. She is quirky and at times is still learning how to play and interact with other dogs. She would be fine as an only dog (can be only dog, does NOT need to be only dog) or a dog her size or bigger. I would not recommend cats or small children … quiet and relaxed is her speed.


Willow has been vet checked, is UTD on shots, spayed, dewormed with Drontal, on Heartgard and Flea/Tick Prevention. She is also microchipped. 

If interested in applying to adopt with us please fill out an application and one of our application processors will contact you as soon as possible. We appreciate your patience.
https://goo.gl/AzrASu

Thank you for saving a life by choosing to adopt :)

animal.description:
Meet Ryder.............a true survivor! He's looking for a dedicated and qualified person who can walk through his healing process with him.

Ryder is a handsome eight-year-old male Pointer/Pit mix who has endured some big-time neglect. However, he also has proven to be on the road to a very happy/healthy recovery. He is such an awesome dog, and given everything he's been through any dog lover would want to get him out of the shelter ASAP. Even the staff realize it’s just not the right environment for Ryder.

Ryder continues to recover physically. He has demonstrated a few situational behavior issues when around strangers. As we advocate for his needs, we are looking for a very particular forever or foster home so he can prosper into new life adventures.

Ryder was found back in April literally boarded up with another dog inside an abandoned car. He was absolutely emaciated and covered head to toe with infected sores and bite wounds from the other dog. Even his poor eyes and the bottoms of his feet were infected. The dogs had both been alone in the car, starving, for who knows how long. Ryder was only about 39 pounds when he was found. A month later, Ryder was up to a healthy 65 pounds. He has been on various medications and treatments over the several months as a team of dedicated people try to get his skin, eyes and paws back to normal. This guy has made HUGE progress and looks like a totally different dog. He's probably going to be recovering, on meds, and needing semi-regular check-ups for a while. He last vet visit was in August. They started him on a new course of antibiotics, eye meds, and skin meds. He has been growly with male veterinarians when he's first met them, although he was fine with them after just a few minutes.

Behaviorally, Ryder is your typical smart, super-goofball Pitbull. He’s very intelligent and eager, lots of healthy energy for his age, good on-leash, totally housebroken, very affectionate and responsive with people he knows. He has done well with most of the other dogs he's met. Ryder is generally more comfortable with women. He has been kennel-reactive to strangers walking by, both male and female. Mostly just barking, but sometimes he will lunge at the gate if the stranger (with a backpack, hat and/or sunglasses) lingers. Since he was a homeless person's dog for the majority of his life, his protectiveness is quite understandable. His triggers will be important to respect as Ryder learns to increase his ability to trust. Potential! Potential! Potential! He’s almost there!
In the right foster or forever home, Ryder is going to do amazingly well! He’s such a great dog when he's in a comfortable setting. Clearly, he has been through many difficult situations. He has not given up!

If interested, please send a brief description of what you can offer Ryder. ellen.second.chance@gmail.com

animal.description:
Meet Chewie. He is about 2 years old.and is being fostered in the Philadelphia area. He's neutered and up to date on his vaccines. He's heartworm negative and available by filling out an adoption application on MAJR.org
Chewie is a sad story. He is a sweet little Jack mix who is around 2. He ended up in a shelter . Because he is cute, he was adopted out several times. He came back twice as a stray and both times the adopters said they didn't want him back . They said he had too much energy and he barked too much.  The third home returned him because the owner said he bit her slipper when she tried to put it on.
Chewie has been with his foster home for about 3 months . When he first came to his foster home, he was a mess. He had no social skills  and seemed to nip the other dogs when he got excited (which he still does but only with one dog and he is learning that is not a good idea).. He was reactive with other dogs but not in a mean way. He just wanted to meet other dogs and didn't know how to react so he overreacted. , He is reactive on a leash and we are working with him on that. He barks in the crate but is relatively quiet outside the crate (he will chortle) and will settle quickly at night in the crate.  He is learning to be a dog and a companion. He is smart but he's like that nerdy kid with the misbuttoned shirt . He would do best in a home with no children and a home that is willing to continue to work with him ...maybe take him to a positive and knowledgeable obedience classes or give him a job like nose work or barn hunting. He is smart but for his first 2 years he was never asked to think and problem solve as a companion. He just needs that time and patience. He is sweet and loves to cuddle and he is willing to share a lap .
MAJR is a small foster based  rescue. We do not have a kennel with visitation hours. If you are interested in adopting a dog from us you must fill out an application and be approved for adoption. Thank you

animal.description:
Hi my name is Baby, but my friends here at MVPC call my Granny. I am not sure why I ended up at the shelter, but let me tell you, it was hard on these old bones. Shelters are no place for any dog, let alone an old gal like me. I have two speeds...nothing and slow. I want to nap and eat. That’s pretty much it. Can you tell taking my picture isn’t a favorite of mine? Food is though. Love food. I am good with other animals, but I am over playing and shenanigans. Cats, dogs, whatever...they are all fine. I just want to lie down and chew on my bones until dinner. I am not a fan of having my nails cut, but other than that, I am not too grumpy. If you just want to exist through life, and eat, I am your girl. Don’t leave food near me though...all’s fair if you walk away. The shelter isn’t too sure what my breed is, so lab was the guess. I was a pretty girl in my hay day, now I am aged and classy.

ADOPTION FEE: $200 (All MVPC dogs are heartworm-tested, completely vetted, spayed/neutered, microchipped, crate-trained and house-trained)

A $100 hold fee is required for approved applications and will be applied to the full adoption fee at the time of the home visit. 
ADOPTER: Dog experience
BIRTHDAY: Estimated 11 years
FENCE: Preferred (an electric fence is not an acceptable form of containment)
DOGS: Yes, but I don’t want to play
CATS: Sure
KIDS: Yes, over 8 please, I am an old lady 

INQUIRIES: ALL inquiries begin with a submitted adoption application, which is found on our website, www.miamivalleypitcrew.com. We do not adopt to individuals under the age of 25. We prefer male/female dog pairings unless both already reside in the home. 

DO NOT: USE THE PETFINDER CONTACT/ADOPT BUTTONS--we are unable to monitor those and you will not receive a response. 

PLEASE NOTE: We are volunteer based and a home visit is required; we have a two-hour adoption radius from Kettering, OH for our adult dogs and 75 miles for our puppies. Exceptions for our ADULT dogs only, though rare, may be made on a case-by-case basis but we must be able to do a home visit. Thank you for your understanding!

animal.description: Interview with Squeaks! 1.WHY DID THEY NAME YOU SQUEAKS? Because when i want to do something i kind of squeak instead of whines. I just cute like dat. 2.HOW ARE YOU SO CUTE?! I dont know...someting called genetics? They arent scary, they dont really tell me what breed i am based on looks, and I cant eat or see them so i dont really know what they is...but they made me cute. 3. WHAT IS YOUR FAVORITE THING TO DO? Walks and pettings and playing with things but mostly snacks and walks ohhh and when my friends come say hi and love me but walks alot....dis is hard one! 4.DO YOU HAVE DOG FRIENDS HERE? At first they are scary and I make sure I stay safe but then when i see they are nice i am very nice too and we are best friends fast and forever. They can't be scary though. I really dont like scary things. 5. WHATS YOUR DREAM HOME? One with all the walks and snacks, and maybe nothing scary...i would really like a comfy bed and lots of loves and maybe i can sleep on the humans bed? I hear some humans like that....Do humans have genetics? I want them to have those too if i have them. We can have a bunch of different ones and celebrate them. OH! I also am kind of nervous of little humans so lets go really slow with those or none of those....i fink they are called kids. 6. WHATS ONE PROMISE YOU MAKE YOUR FUTURE HOME? To always try my best and always love dem and never to give up on dem. Adopt this cute guy today! Hes just too precious!

animal.description:
Sully is a 7 year old Golden / Labrador Retriever mix, approximately 75 pounds, up-to-date on vaccines & neutered.  He is an active pre-senior super smart loyal boy with moderate activity level! He likes daily walks and would enjoy a game of ball. After proper exercise, he is happy to settle in with his people.

Sully’s future family will greatly benefit from participating in training classes and his trainer will offer a complimentary training session to his new family. He wants to please and is oh so smart! He loves routine physical activity and truly wants to hang out with responsible people who are very invested in his happiness.  Sully would prefer to be in a single pet home with no small children.  He is making great progress on his leash skills in his foster/trainer's home and he has been learning how to just kick-back & trust. He is enjoying that calmness. A nutritious quality dog food is a must because he is prone to allergies. His previous skin inflammation has decreased with his brand new diet. Please go to Lucky Paws Rescue web site (the Tacoma rescue) and fill out the Lucky Paws’ application. Specific questions can go to ellen.second.chance@gmail.com

PLEASE NOTE: Sully is N0T a match for people who are gone more than three hours a day, apartments, a family cat, unfenced yard, children under 12, people who do not have dog experience & /or are not routinely physically active.
